<HEADLINE> BAe, Lockheed Cooperate on Battlefield Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- British Aerospace (BAe) and
Lockheed Martin of the US have joined forces to bid for a 5
billion US dollars contract to supply battlefield reconnaissance
vehicles for the British and US armies.
</P>
<P>
The contract is a big step forward in defense cooperation
between Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
BAe and Lockheed will form a joint venture company to handle
the bid, with armored vehicle makers Vickers and Alvis from the
UK and General Dynamics Land Systems of the US acting as main
contractors to the company.
</P>
<P>
They decided to pool the contract last year and are expected to
order about 1,600 vehicles -- 1,200 for the US Army and the rest
for British Army.
</P>
<P>
The vehicles officially are under the name Tracer/FSCS and the
cost of each vehicle comes to more than 3 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Britain, the new vehicles would replace the Army's aging
Scorpion and Scimitar vehicles, neither of which proved efficient
machines in the Gulf and Bosnian conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The powerful alliance is reported likely to be opposed by a
team including GKN Defense and GEC-Marconi in the UK with US
partners which have yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
However, military sources here believe that it is unlikely that
other bidders will emerge because no other British company is
thought to be capable of supplying the technology and integration
systems for the highly complex machines.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Lockheed Matin said that Tracer would be
designed to enter the battle theater ahead of the main battle
groups and gather intelligence through digital electronic
"sniffing, seeing and hearing" systems.
</P>
<P>
The armored vehicles will also be a radar-avoiding "stealth"
vehicle, designed to penetrate far behind enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
It will be packed with sophisticated radar, infra-red and visual
sensors, and carry massive computing power and state-of-the-art
communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
BAe said that the Joint Requirements Operations Committee of
the US and British armies was scheduled to meet soon to hammer out
Tracer's technical requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
