<HEADLINE> 4,000 Soldiers Ready for Evacuation of Westerners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- About 4,000 Western soldiers are now
in Congo and off the coast of Zaire to prepare for the evacuation
of 7,800 Western expatriates from Zaire, after the arrival of the
U.S. helicopter-carrier "USS Nassau" off the coast of Zaire,
Agence France-Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
On board the USS Nassau are 1,800 U.S. marines who are
preparing to evacuate the 350 U.S. citizens staying in Zaire,
according to the Pentagon, which said that the deployment of U.S.
soldiers is purely for the purpose of evacuation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 600 U.S. soldiers are stationed in Brazzaville,
which is separated from Kinshasa by the Zaire River, and they can
call for aid from the 300 U.S. soldiers in Libreville, Gabon, and
even the U.S. rapid reaction force in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Equipped with Chinook and Cobra military helicopters and
Harrier combat aircraft, the USS Nassau can serve as the basis
for a reinforced infantry battalion of the U.S. Army, and has
already served in the evacuation of U.S. citizens from Albania.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, the former colonial power in Zaire, has sent a
parachutist battalion of 550 soldiers to Brazzaville and the
Congolese port of Pointe-Noire, 350 kilometers west of the
Congolese capital.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian troops are equipped with five C-130 transport
aircraft and can evacuate the 2,800 Belgians living in Zaire,
1,000 of whom are in the southeastern province of Shaba.
</P>
<P>
France has sent 300 soldiers to Congo, and has 600 soldiers
regularly based in Libreville. The French troops have two Puma
military helicopters and some boats in Congo and two Transall
C-160 transport planes in Gabon.
</P>
<P>
Two thousand French nationals are living in Zaire, 900 of whom
are in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Britain has sent about 60 commandos of the Royal
Marine to Brazzaville. They are equipped with hovercraft and speed
boats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
