<HEADLINE> National Youth Policy Urged in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's African
National Congress Youth League (ANCYL) today appealed to the
government to endorse a national youth policy to help find ways
for youths to participate in the country's development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a youth conference here, ANCYL secretary for youth
development Songezo Mjongeli said the lack of such national youth
policy would affect South Africa's economic growth because their
participation in economic development was vital.
</P>
<P>
Mjongeli said the goals of the conference were to reduce
unemployment among the youth, and to provide another chance for
youth who had missed out on education and training; equitable
access to health and a better quality of life of all young
people.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from South Africa's all nine provinces are working
on a draft youth policy on the economy, human resources
development, peace and security, international relations, the
criminal justice system and the environment.
</P>
<P>
On human resources development, the draft said apartheid
produced a distorted skills profile based on racism.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, most Whites were given opportunities to
acquire formal skills through universities and technical schools
or through an apprenticeship system.
</P>
<P>
While the majority of Blacks acquired training informally and
the skills they acquired were usually not recognized.
</P>
<P>
The draft also called for emphasis on better results in
teaching numeracy, maths and natural sciences, especially in
previously disadvantaged schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
