<HEADLINE> Bank of England Chief Issues Warning over EMU Timetable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Eddie George, governor of the Bank
of England, has warned that forcing the European Monetary Union
(EMU) to go ahead according to a timetable rather than economic
convergence criteria would be fraught with danger.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht Treaty, the single European currency would
be launched on January 1 1999, but most of the 15 members of the
European Union (EU) were unlikely to meet the strict entry
criteria in time, according to financial experts.
</P>
<P>
"My sympathies remain with those who emphasize the importance
of sustainable convergence, rather than the calendar," the
Financial Times quoted George as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"What really puzzles me is why anyone should want to risk
joining the euro area unless they were genuinely convinced that
the economic risks had been minimized through sustainable
convergence," he said.
</P>
<P>
The governor made it clear that Britain, which has won an
opt-out right on the single currency, remained committed to the
monetary and fiscal stability demanded by the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
If the British government finally decided to stay out of the
single currency, it would be crucial to persevere with those
disciplines, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
