<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Renews Call for Conducting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu today repeated his call on the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) for concluding the final-status talks within six
months.
</P>
<P>
At today's cabinet meeting, Netanyahu called for an immediate
start of the final-status talks in order to solve all the current
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reviewed a proposal being formulated by the United
States on resuming the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace talks,
which is based on the idea of conducting the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that, if the two sides failed to reach
agreement within six months, he is willing to attend a Camp David
style summit with PNA President Yasser Arafat under the auspices
of U.S. President Bill Clinton, so as to solve the outstanding
issues.
</P>
<P>
In September 1978, former U.S. President Jimmy Carter hosted
at the Camp David a historic summit between late Israeli Prime
Minister Menachem Begin and Egyptian President Anwar Sadat. Begin
and Sadat signed two peace agreements on normalizing bilateral
ties, thereby sealing the Israeli-Egyptian peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with German Television earlier today,
Netanyahu reaffirmed his stand that the talks should not begin
before the PNA halts the current wave of violence.
</P>
<P>
"I put forward the proposal, that once the violence is
stopped, to go towards the final-settlement negotiations for six
months," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If it is not resolved within six months, (it is time) for
Arafat and myself and President Clinton to meet in a Camp David
style summit, or to try to get finally one big effort to (achieve)
the resolution of the Israeli-Palestinian disputes," he added.
</P>
<P>
On March 19, a day after Israel began the controversial Har
Homa settlement construction in East Jerusalem, Netanyahu first
proposed holding the final-status talks and concluding the
negotiations within six months rather than two years as
stipulated in the Oslo accords between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
But the PNA rejected the proposal as a tactic to divert the
world attention from the Har Homa construction. PNA spokesman Abu
Rudeineh said the Palestinian side will not accept the proposal
simply because of its lack of trust in the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
By repeating his call for holding the final-status talks,
Netanyahu was apparently making a diplomatic gesture on the eve of
his upcoming U.S. visit. He is scheduled to depart Sunday for a
three-day U.S. trip, during which he will meet with Jordanian King
Hussein and Clinton on defusing the current Israeli-Palestinian
crisis, triggered by the Har Homa Jewish settlement construction.
</P>
<P>
The final-status talks will tackle the most difficult and
sensitive issues on the final borders, status of Jerusalem and
fate of Palestinian refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
