<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Unemployment Rate Down to 5.2 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment rate in the U.S.
declined for the second consecutive month to 5.2 percent in March,
U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was the lowest seasonally adjusted jobless rate in five
months and it followed the rate of 5.3 percent in February and 5.4
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The report said that employers reported a moderate increase of
175,000 in jobs after gains of 293,000 in February and 259,000 in
January.
</P>
<P>
The job growth in March was led by service industries such as
computer and data processing, retailing and banks and securities.
Manufacturing employment rose by 16,000 while construction
employment, which had shot up by 108,000 in February, fell 27,000
in March.
</P>
<P>
While job growth last month was moderate, average hourly wages
in the country rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
The report said that average hourly earnings of non-farm,
non-supervisory workers rose by 0.4 percent to 12.15 dollars in
March after an identical gain in February.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, average wages in the U.S. are up 4 percent
but that hasn't translated into an increase in inflation which was
3.3 percent in last year.
</P>
<P>
With other signs the economy's strength is extending into the
Spring, many economists believe the U.S. unemployment rate could
slip below 5 percent later this year for the first time in a
quarter century.
</P>
<P>
The White House welcomes the news today as a sign of "a healthy
economy".
</P>
<P>
But Wall Street took the report as another sign that the U.S.
Federal Reserve will have to raise interest rates again, resulting
in a brief falling of more than 70 points in the Dow Jones
industrial average in early trading today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
