<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Hold Conference on Trafficking in Women in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- As President of the European Union,
the Netherlands is organizing a ministerial conference dealing with
international trafficking in women.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the conference, due to be held from 24 to 26 April in
The Hague, is to bring about recommendations for a code of conduct
to prevent and combat trafficking in women, the Dutch EU presidency
said on Friday in a press release.
</P>
<P>
This is a follow-up to the Fourth World Women's Conference in
Beijing in 1995 and the European Conference on Trafficking in Women
held in Vienna in 1996, the Presidency said.
</P>
<P>
The themes to be discussed at the conference, which will be
attended by ministers of Equal Rights, Justice and Home Affairs of
EU member states, are the prevention, detection and prosecution of
those involved in trafficking in women.
</P>
<P>
According to an estimate made by the International Organization
for Migration, in 1995 some 500,000 women were trafficked to the EU.
Many of these women came from Eastern Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
