<HEADLINE> US Pentagon Says Cost of F-22 Program Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen today defended the F-22 program despite of its higher cost
than previously projected.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the U.S. NBC's "Today" show, Cohen
said, "we need planes such as the F-22... in order to be able to
carry out our mission."
</P>
<P>
However, critics have indicated that there is no threat from
any enemy that requires the U.S. to deploy the sophisticated and
expensive F-22 fighters.
</P>
<P>
In a letter made public Thursday, Cohen told congressmen that
the latest Pentagon estimate of the F-22 is 33 percent higher than
the earlier Air Force projection.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force says 438 of the radar-evading fighters will
cost 43.8 billion U.S. dollars while Cohen's advisers put the
figure at 64.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force insists that program costs can be cut. But Cohen
warned that "such reductions might not be achieved." 
</P>
</TEXT>
