<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party, UF Informal Talks Stalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Informal consultations among
major Indian parties to resolve the political crisis facing the
10-month-old H.D. Deve Gowda government were stalled today
following a hardening of posture both by the Congress party and
the ruling United Front (UF), the Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis arose out of the Congress party's withdrawal
of support for the 14-party UF government on March 30, a move
which reduced the government to a minority.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party staked its claim to form an alternative
government soon after it withdrew support for the UF.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister V.P. Singh, who has been trying to broker
peace between the Congress party and the UF in the past few days
in order to keep the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) out
of power, said today that he stood by the UF resolution -- "no
support to the Congress party and no change in UF leadership."
</P>
<P>
The Congress party today sharpened its attack on Prime Minister
Deve Gowda, with senior party leader K. Karunakaran making Gowda's
resignation a precondition for the party to review its decision to
withdraw support for the UF government.
</P>
<P>
"Gowda should be replaced. Only then we will consider the UF
appeal to us," he said, referring to the UF's request that the
Congress party review its decision to scrap support to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Karunakaran, a member of the Congress Working Committee which
is the highest decision making body of the Congress party, was
part of the core group which took the decision that support to the
Deve Gowda government be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UF today ruled out sharing power with the
Congress party, but said it had an "open mind" on the modalities
of the talks with the party.
</P>
<P>
In response to the Congress party's insistence on Gowda's
resignation, a UF spokesman reiterated the stand taken by the UF
Steering Committee that the leadership issue of the UF was
non-negotiable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
