<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British and U.S. Arms Makers to Cooperate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A British arms maker will join
hands with a leading United States arms producer in bidding
for a battlefield vehicle supply contract for the troops of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The 5 billion U.S. dollar deal to supply state-of-the-art
battlefield reconnaissance vehicles, Tracer/FSCS, is seen as a big
step toward defense cooperation between Britain and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
British Aerospace (BAe) and U.S. Lockheed Martin will form a
joint venture to handle the bid, with armored vehicle makers
Vickers and Alvis from Britain and General Dynamics Land Systems
from the U.S. acting as main contractors to the company.
</P>
<P>
They decided to pool the contract last year and are expected to
order about 1,600 vehicles -- 1,200 for the U.S. Army and 400 for
the British Army.
</P>
<P>
BAe said that the Joint Requirements Operations Committee of
the U.S. and British armies would meet soon to define Tracer's
technical requirements. The vehicles are estimated at more than 3
million U.S. dollars each.
</P>
<P>
Britain would use the new vehicles to replace its aging
Scorpion and Scimitar vehicles, which proved inefficient in the
Gulf and Bosnian conflicts.
</P>
<P>
British GKN Defense and GEC-Marconi reportedly would challenge
the two companies in the bid.
</P>
<P>
However, military sources here believe that it is unlikely that
other bidders will emerge because no other British company is
thought to be capable of supplying the technology and integration
systems for the highly complex machines.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Lockheed Martin said that Tracer would be a
radar-avoiding "stealth" vehicle, designed to penetrate far behind
enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
It will be packed with sophisticated radar, infra-red and
visual sensors, and carry massive computing power and
state-of-the-art communications equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
