<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP to Deliver Emergency Food Aid to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) will
deliver 420 tons of food donated by the Italian government to
Albania soon in a joint operation launched today by WFP and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The food, including flour, beans and vegetable oil, can feed
7,500 people for four months, a WFP press release said.
</P>
<P>
The food will be delivered to orphanages, hospitals, homes for
the elderly and centers for the handicapped in the capital city of
Tirana, as well as the northern and central Albania's towns of
Skoder and Kavaje and Lushnje and Fier in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
The WFP said the food would also go to the poorest households
affected by the collapse of the social welfare system.
</P>
<P>
"It will be the first United Nations delivery of food to
Albania since the serious political crisis erupted in March," the
WFP said.
</P>
<P>
The first shipment is expected to arrive at the port of Durres
early next week and the distribution will be carried out by the
Albanian Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs and some
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, preparations for a much larger emergency food aid
operation are underway, the WFP added.
</P>
<P>
It said the current wheat requirement in Albania is estimated
at 700,000 tons. In Albania which is one of the poorest countries
in Europe, urban residents rely heavily on food imports as only 4
percent of domestic production enters the market.
</P>
<P>
During a recent week-long visit to Albania, a WFP assessment
mission has found that the country's food-supply infrastructure
has been largely destroyed or being out of function due to
security fears among workers.
</P>
<P>
"The current food crisis in Albania has been further aggravated
by the closure of its borders, which has made it impossible to
import food," WFP Executive Director Catherine Bertini said.
</P>
<P>
"Humanitarian relief is essential if we are to avoid a further
aggravation of social tensions," Bertini said.
</P>
<P>
Food prices in Albania have risen by 40 percent after the
recent disturbances, said the WFP, while wheat production in 1996
dropped nearly 26 percent from 1995 to about 300,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
