<HEADLINE> Chinese NGO Official on Protection of Women's Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The conference on human rights
should pay more attention to the elimination of poverty and
discrimination and violence against women, a Chinese NGO
representative said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ongoing session of the United Nations Human
Rights Commission, Feng Cui, an official from the All-China
Women's Federation (ACWF), said the commission should adjust its
work priority so that it can reflect the wishes and demands of the
broad masses of people including women.
</P>
<P>
She accused a few western countries of deliberately distorting
the concept of human rights, pursuing double standard instead of
taking an impartial and objective attitude, creating confrontation
instead of promoting cooperation, and even using the human rights
issue as a tool to attack other sovereign countries.
</P>
<P>
Feng urged the Human Rights Commission to take measures to stop
and correct this abnormal situation as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
She hoped the international community will help the NGOs of the
developing countries participate in the international human rights
activities so that their aspirations and demands could be
presented to the commission.
</P>
<P>
She called on NGOs to play an active role in monitoring
government activities in international cooperation regarding human
rights.
</P>
<P>
She said that ACWF, the largest women NGO in China, has
actively participated in international and domestic activities
aimed at promoting and protecting women's human rights.
</P>
<P>
Feng said the ACWF has been involved in a series of human
rights-related activities, such as literacy programs,
poverty-eliminating projects, re-employment programs, and
political empowerment campaign among women in China's rural and
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
She said these activities had effectively safeguarded the human
rights of women and children and raised the awareness of the whole
society on gender equality as a follow-up to the Fourth World
Conference on Women held in Beijing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"All these activities have produced great impact on the
promotion and protection of women's human rights," Feng said.
</P>
</TEXT>
