<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Court Orders Renault to Suspend Closure of Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A French court today ordered the
automaker Renault to suspend the procedure to close its Vilvoorde
assembly plant in Belgium, which will result in the layoff of
3,100 workers.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal of Grand Instance of Nanterre outside Paris, where
the office of social affairs department of Renault is located,
asked Renault to stop "pursuing the application of the closure of
the Vilvoorde plant until it has fulfilled its duty of information
and consultation with its Committee of European Group."
</P>
<P>
The decision followed an earlier decision this week by a
Belgian court in Brussels declaring the procedure by Renault to
close the Vilvoorde plant as illegal in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The court in Nanterre also ordered Renault to pay 15,000 francs
(3,000 U.S. dollars) to the Committee of the European Group, an
employees' consultation institution for all the Renault plants in
Europe, for failing to make consultation with it when making the
decision.
</P>
<P>
Renault have decided to make appeals against the two rulings by
the courts, and said that "the elements of procedure will not
change the economic necessities which impose themselves upon the
enterprise," reported Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Renault has been losing money for years and is planning a large
scale social restructuring of its industrial sector to make itself
more competitive in European and world auto market.
</P>
<P>
Renault's labor unions in France, Spain and Belgium, which have
been holding trans-national European protests since Renault
announced the decision in late February, today welcomed the court
rulings.
</P>
<P>
From 500 to 1,000 Renault workers from Vilvoorde today
demonstrated in Brussels in an "over-charged atmosphere" in
front of the headquarters of the European Commission, where the
European commissioner for competition, Karel van Miert, met with
representatives of the workers, according to AFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eurotunnel Unveils New Safety Procedures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Eurotunnel, the Anglo-French
Channel tunnel operator, unveiled new safety procedures Thursday
in the wake of last November's Channel tunnel fire and confirmed
that it would re-open freight shuttle services in June.
</P>
<P>
The safety improvements announced Thursday include more checks
on lorries, stopping trains in the tunnel as soon as a fire is
discovered rather than attempting to drive out, installing water
sprinklers in the tunnel, adding electronic devices to show more
precisely where a train has stopped, and providing smoke hoods for
truck drivers and train crew.
</P>
<P>
However, the company confirmed that it had no intention of
enclosing its controversial open lattice-sided lorry shuttle
wagons and rejected suggestions that the semi-open structure of
the wagons had contributed significantly to the spread of the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Ponsolle, Eurotunnel co-chairman, said: "We don't think
absolute safety is possible but we have learned lessons from this
incident and have already implemented a number of important
changes".
</P>
<P>
But the Fire Brigade Union accused the company of putting
passengers' lives at risk, warning that its refusal to change the
wagons was complacency at its worst and that a future, fatal fire
was "an absolute certainty".
</P>
<P>
The new measures are expected to cost 20 million pounds (32.8
million US dollars) in new equipment and 1-2 million pounds
(1.64-3.28 million US dollars) a year in additional staff costs
and staff training.
</P>
<P>
A decision on whether Eurotunnel's plans are adequate will be
taken next month by the Channel Tunnel Safety Authority, a joint
British and French body responsible for regulating the operation
of the tunnel. But Eurotunnel said it was confident there would be
no problems.
</P>
<P>
Eurotunnel hopes that the freight shuttles, which were
transporting 2,000 wagons a day before the fire, can be resumed in
June after tunnel repairs are complete.
</P>
<P>
Last year's fire has so far cost about 75 million pounds (123
million US dollars) in lost revenue. But the cost to the company
will be about 10 million pounds (16.4 million US dollars) with the
rest covered by insurers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
