<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turk Charged with Setting Blaze That Killed His Wife, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish man was arrested today and
charged with deliberately setting a blaze in his own apartment in
the western German city of Krefeld on Monday which killed his wife
and two of his children, German media reported.
</P>
<P>
German investigators said the 42-year-old Turk, identified as
Aziz Demir had started the fire after his wife had told him she
would file for divorce following the March 28-31 Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out in Krefeld at about 02:00 hours Monday
forced Demir's 41-year-old wife and one of his daughter to jump to
deaths from a three-floor window of their apartment. The son of
the couple was found dead later in the flat, dying from smoke
inhalation.
</P>
<P>
Demir had claimed to have been at a bar when the fire broke
out. He had to be refrained by the police from rushing into the
burning house after returning home at about 02:30 hours.
</P>
<P>
But German investigators said they had obtained a video film
from a petrol station security camera showing him filling a petrol
canister three hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
According to police in Krefeld, two witnesses also saw Demir
carrying the petrol canister and heading for his apartment
building later.
</P>
<P>
German prosecutors said Demir, who has worked in Germany for 20
years, had regularly beaten his wife and children. To avoid their
father, the children had even slept out in the family car.
</P>
<P>
The wife had been preparing for a divorce and had moved money
to Turkey, they added.
</P>
<P>
The deadly family drama has soured relations between Germany
and Turkey this week, with Turkish government officials reportedly
accusing Germany of tolerating ring-wing attacks against Muslim.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's ambassador to Germany, Volkan Vural, was summoned to
Germany Foreign Ministry on Thursday to receive a letter from the
Bonn government rejecting the accusations.
</P>
<P>
Vural in an interview with a German television Friday that
there had been "misunderstandings" between Ankara and Bonn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Council Urges Zaire to Allow Access to Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today called on all the parties, especially the Alliance of
Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire, to allow aid
agencies free access to refugees and displaced persons in eastern
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Council President Antonio Monteiro of Portugal said that the
council was deeply concerned with the serious humanitarian
situation in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"The council fully shares the concerns of the (U.N.)
secretary-general expressed yesterday as well as the joint appeal
issued today by the European Union, UNHCR and UNICEF," he said in
a statement to press.
</P>
<P>
The six-month-old civil war has driven countless Rwandan
refugees and local people into the interior. Numerous people have
already died or are dying of exhaustion, hunger and disease. Over
the past week, the United Nations Higher Commissioner for
Refugees, United Nations Children's Fund and the World Food
Program and other aid agencies are trying to aid more than 100,000
refugees who have re-emerged from the forest. The aid agencies
estimate that more displaced persons remain out of reach.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council urges all parties in Zaire to enable aid
workers to reach and assist refugees and displaced persons among
whom are thousands of children, Monteiro said.
</P>
<P>
"They need help -- and they need it now," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
