<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-04 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mediterranean Red Cross Conference Ends in Tunis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Seventh Conference of the
Mediterranean Red Cross Organizations ended here this afternoon
with the endorsement of "the Tunis Declaration."
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration, work for widening the scope of
human code principles and ensuring respect for human dignity must
be strengthened to serve the interests of the Middle East peoples.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also stipulated that immigrants' rights,
safety, health and interests should be protected.
</P>
<P>
The environment of the Middle East countries should
also be protected, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The declaration pointed out that the red cross organizations
should seek to find mechanisms that help them play a more active
role in environment protection through data exchange and
establishing "an environmental culture."
</P>
<P>
The participants also called for working out an integrated
cooperation plan with a view to turn the Mediterranean basin into
an arena of exchanges and civilizational mingling among the
region's red cross organizations.
</P>
<P>
A Mediterranean Youth Charter was also endorsed at the
conference to increase cooperation and communication among the
region's youths and back up their participation in decision-making
and expertise exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The participants decided that France will host the eighth
conference of the Mediterranean Red Cross and Organizations,
slated to be held in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
