<HEADLINE> Simitis: Balkan Needs Comprehensive Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
today stressed the need for Balkan countries to have a
comprehensive action plan in order to overcome the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Simitis made the remark while attending the two-day conference
of the European Socialist Party (ESP) on the Balkans, which opened
today in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
He said the European Union (EU) did not yet have an all-round
policy which would effectively support the Balkan countries during
this fluid period of transition to the free market economy, and
called on EU countries to assume their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the first priority was the provision of
emergency aid so as to achieve economic stabilization and
consolidate the hopeful political solutions which were already on
course.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the mobilization and intervention of other
international organizations, such as the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), the Western European Union, the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), as well as the
governments of all countries that directly or indirectly influence
developments in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that countries in central and eastern Europe
should be treated equally. He was referring to the countries'
membership bid for the entry into the EU and NATO.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference shortly before the opening of
the conference, ESP President Rudolf Scharping said stability in
the Balkans was a prerequisite for security in the whole of Europe
and the ESP was in favor of political dialogue for the resolution
of the crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Dialogue among the political forces of the Balkans could play a
"decisive role" in developments in the region, he said, adding
that otherwise they would face a wave of conflicts. 
</P>
