<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Government Endeavors to Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government led by
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has come up with a new package for
farmers this week, doling out big concessions aimed at improving
agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Agriculture Convention Thursday attended by
thousands of farmers, the prime minister vowed to bring "green
revolution" in the country by taking concrete steps to make
Pakistan self-sufficient in agricultural produce.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector plays a pivotal role in Pakistan's
economy, contributing almost a quarter of the national income.
</P>
<P>
However, the sector has not received due attention during the
last three decades or more as a result of long-running political
instability, which often resulted in frequent changes of
governments and inconsistent implementation of farm policies.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, as an agricultural country, is now facing a serious
crisis, particularly the acute shortage of wheat, sugar and edible
oil.
</P>
<P>
The Sharif government, which came to power on February 17, is
now attaching great importance to this vital sector and has lost
no time in launching an incentive agricultural package.
</P>
<P>
The package carries a hike in support prices of wheat, rice and
edible oil besides a slash in agricultural input, increases in the
allocation of loans for farmers and solid measures for improving
irrigation infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The new government will also carry out extensive agro-research
and improve infrastructure including construction of road networks
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The package has been widely welcomed and has been termed by
some agricultural experts as "a historic step" to stabilize the
agricultural sector which is the base line of Pakistan's national
economy.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that comprehensive efforts to revive the
unstable agricultural sector are imperative when Pakistan, once
dubbed a "food granary" of the sub-continent, has been importing
two million tons of wheat or more during the last three years, and
the import of wheat for the current year is to cost a massive 25
billion rupees (625 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition, edible oil, sugar, dairy products and a variety of
vegetables in short supply have been imported along with meat,
accounting for 25 percent of the total import bills of the
country, which is already facing an acute balance of payments
problem.
</P>
<P>
Successive governments in Pakistan have treated enhancement of
agricultural production as a bureaucratic exercise of fixing
targets without achieving any meaningful result, Agriculture
Minister Abida Hussain said in her speech delivered at Thursday's
convention.
</P>
<P>
The budgetary allocation to the agricultural sector, which
contributes 24 percent of Pakistan's national income, is less than
5 percent of development expenditures each year.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that inadequate public investment, high cost of
maintenance and wrong-headed price policies in Pakistan are the
major causes of these problems.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the deterioration in the physical integrity of the
irrigation and drainage system and quality of soils has also posed
a serious threat to the sustainability of agricultural growth in
the country.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that due to the continued neglect of irrigation
infrastructure, 70 percent of water is lost in the delivery system
besides the twin menaces of waterlogging and salinity which
continue to damage soil productivity.
</P>
<P>
On the policy front, agriculture experts here are of the view
that the most serious problem is the imbalance between input and
output prices, which reduces farmers' income, fuels ballooning
import bills and encourages smuggling of local produce to the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural package will be helpful in reducing the import
bills of wheat and edible oil, they said. And massive increases in
the support prices of wheat, rice and sunflower seed are expected
to play an active role in increasing areas for the cultivation of
these crops.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the abolition of 12.5 percent sales tax on cotton
seed will give relief to cotton growers, and reduction in the duty
on agricultural machinery would be helpful in introducing modern
techniques.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the package is fairly comprehensive and
should help ease some of the immediate and short-term problems
confronting the country's agricultural sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
