<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Pay Respect to Ancestors at Qingming Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of Chinese from
home and abroad gathered to pay their respects to one of their
forefathers before his majestic tomb on the upper reaches of the
Yellow River today, a day known as "Qingming" on which Chinese
traditionally remember their deceased, mostly family members and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
A grand, solemn ceremony was staged before the tomb of the
Yellow Emperor at Huangling (Yellow Mausoleum) County in Northwest
China's Shaanxi Province. The event was supervised by State
Councillor Song Jian and Wang Zhaoguo, vice chairman of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
At 9:50 a.m., drummers in ethnic costumes beat their drums 32
times, signifying China's 34 provinces, municipalities, autonomous
regions and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
and the Macao Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The resonant drum beats were followed by 12 rings from a bell,
which symbolized the 1.2 billion Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Amid the slow-rhythmed ancient Chinese music of bamboo and
string instruments, visitors placed wreaths and bowed at the 3.6-m
tall mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
Philip Wong Yu-hong, vice chairman of the Chinese General
Chamber of Commerce of Hong Kong and member of the preparatory
committee of the HKSAR, told Xinhua that he felt excited being
back in Shaanxi after a period of three years, particularly when
Hong Kong is about to return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"On this special occasion, I believe that all of us here feel
the same," the 59-year-old man said. "The return of Hong Kong
marks not just the beginning of an epoch of "one country, two
systems" for Hong Kong, but also a starting point for all of the
Chinese people to march toward a unified and strong China."
</P>
<P>
Also in the crowd was Henry Hu Hung-lick, a renowned attorney
from Hong Kong and also a member of the Standing Committee of the
CPPCC, and his wife.
</P>
<P>
Marveling at a giant tree believed to have been planted 5,000
years ago by the Yellow Emperor himself, the 77-year-old Hung-lick
expressed his hope that the ritual for the Yellow Emperor would
continue, saying "the activity can encourage all Chinese people to
contribute to the cause of reunifying the country."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the city of Baoji, also in Shaanxi Province, a
similar event was held by the local government to remember the Yan
Emperor, another Chinese ancestor. Historical records and legends
hold that the Yan Emperor was born here 5,000 years ago. The
Chinese people sometimes refer to themselves as "descendents of
the Yan and Yellow emperors."
</P>
<P>
Exactly 1997 pigeons were let into the air, marking China's
resumption of exercising sovereignty over Hong Kong. Artistic
performances were given and more than 1,000 people took part in a
5,000-m foot race.
</P>
<P>
According to legend, numerous tribes lived on the vast and
rugged Chinese land some 5,000 years ago. Two major tribes, headed
separately by the Yellow Emperor and the Yan Emperor, fought and
later merged, along with other smaller tribes, into an early
version of the Chinese ethnic population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
