<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA: Peace Process on Verge of Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has warned, in an urgent message to U.S. President
Bill Clinton, that the Israeli-Palestinian peace process was on
the verge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
The PNA sent the message on the eve of the Sunday visit by
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is to travel Sunday to the U.S. on a three-day
working visit and will meet with Jordanian King Hussein who is
currently in the U.S. undergoing a prostate surgery in Rochester,
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Netanyahu will meet with the U.S. president and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to discuss ways of
defusing the Israeli-Palestinian tension.
</P>
<P>
The message said if the current crisis continued, the forces
of peace would be left behind and forces of violence would be
pushed to the fore, which meant the eruption of an all-out
confrontation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
In the message, the PNA demanded the U.S. government to put
more pressure on Israel to change its hardline policies that
have led to the deadlock in the peace process and to the current
wave of violence.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat convened in Gaza Friday night a
joint meeting of the Executive Committee of the Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO) and the PNA cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The meeting dealt with the current situation and the resolution
adopted in Cairo, Egypt, last week by the Arab League's Foreign
Ministers Meeting to recommend freezing ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Abu Rudeineh, PNA cabinet secretary, said Israel should halt
the controversial Har Homa construction in East Jerusalem before
an Arafat-Netanyahu summit could take place.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Netanyahu's proposal to immediately resume
and conclude within six months the final-status talks, Rudeineh
said the PNA was studying all proposals on resuming the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed the PNA was skeptical, in the absence of its
trust for the Netanyahu government, if Israel's proposal was
enough to bring back the stalled peace process on track.
</P>
<P>
Saying the PNA was still waiting for the U.S. initiative to
break the peace stalemate, Rudeineh urged Clinton to guarantee
Israel's commitments to the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is reportedly formulating a new proposal on
restarting the Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations based on
the idea of reviving the final-status peace talks, which will
tackle the most difficult issues of the final borders, status of
Jerusalem and Palestinian refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
