<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Early Retirement Package Sparks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Sense of insecurity among workers
in the money-losing public sectors abounds as Egypt's early
retirement renumeration package prepares to hit the road, the
English weekly Al-Ahram reported in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, approved by the cabinet's ad-hoc committee on
privatization on March 23, is designed to encourage early
retirement in the ailing public sector enterprises and cushion
the shocking waves of privatization.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, men between the ages of 50-58 and women
between 45-58, who have been employed for at least 20 years, are
eligible for early retirement in return for a lump sum payment
ranging between 12,000 and 35,000 Egyptian pounds (about 3,529
and 10,294 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, chairman of the committee,
has held that the scheme will balance the interests of the
employees and their stumbling companies.
</P>
<P>
However, many argue, instead of giving extra reparations to
the would-be pensioners, the plan actually reduces the sum that
will have been payable if a full period of service is completed.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Mursi, secretary-general of the Trade Union
Federation, speculated that a worker that quits before the age of
45 will get a pension 15 percent less than his due at a normal
retirement age.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, a worker retiring at 50 will settle for a sum 10
percent less than his normal pay, and 5 percent less for a
55-year-old retiree.
</P>
<P>
Though the gap narrows with a longer stay, it hardly makes a
big improvement on the pensioner's future job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The government scheme makes no satisfactory allowance for the
future of workers, many of whom have never known much about any
career move before, said Saad El-Din Khalifa, commercial
consultant for a state-owned wood factory.
</P>
<P>
"By the time they are in their fifties, they are unable to
work in any other place because their skills are limited by the
physically challenging nature of their jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Khalifa offered his recipe for the problem
of excess employment in the public sector, saying that companies
should encourage workers to become their shareholders, or set up
a certain social insurance fund.
</P>
<P>
Giving not even a lukewarm welcome to the plan, public sector
workers feared that the government is taking more than it gives.
</P>
<P>
A worker at the Egyptian Company for the Manufacture of Wood,
who earns 85 pounds (25 dollars) a month, said that he prefers
what he is getting now, a small but day-to-day payment, to the
promised compensation which "amounts to nothing" for him.
</P>
<P>
"To take one lump sum that could be very easily lost in an
unsuccessful venture is too risky. My future would be over," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Another worker said on condition of anonymity that he even
doubted that the ceiling compensation money would be enough to
cover one serious surgical operation once he is no longer covered
by the company's medical insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
Most of the company's employees agreed that the funds had
better be spent on the purchase of new equipment and guaranteeing
the regular supply of raw material.
</P>
<P>
Such a policy, they argue, can save their company, and in a
real sense, their own jobs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some experts pointed out that the ailing companies
are going bankrupt because of bad management and lack of
efficiency, but not of overemployment.
</P>
<P>
They suggest that certain investment on the workers, such as
on-the-job training and re-education, would guarantee a more
capable workforce, if not a bigger workforce.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment in the country of 62 million people has reached
17.5 percent, according to the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Speaking in this vein, Gouda Abdel-Khalek, professor of
economics at the Cairo University, urges the allocation of funds
to retrain workers and alleviate their transitional doldrums.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he warned, they would be left facing a competitive
and aggressive market with little preparation or relief.
</P>
<P>
The early retirement package will be implemented in
unprofitable and stumbling companies at the moment.
</P>
<P>
The top 15 depressed companies affiliated to the public
business sector owe 1.5 billion pounds (441.2 million dollars) in
addition to the same sum in interests, according to Public
Enterprise Atef Ebeid. The majority of them are in the spinning
and weaving, chemicals and metallurgical sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
