<HEADLINE> Calm in South Lebanon Despite Israeli Air Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A relative calm still shrouds south
Lebanon today despite a dawn air raid carried out by Israeli
military helicopters at suspected targets of Lebanese Muslim
guerrillas, security sources in the area reported.
</P>
<P>
They said that the Israeli helicopters fired three
air-to-surface missiles at vicinities of the village of Lebbayyah
in Western Beqaa without causing casualties or damages.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters also swept with machineguns the heights of
Jebel Al-Zahr and the vicinities of Lebbayyah and Ein Al-Fjour.
</P>
<P>
The air raid followed reconnaissance flights of Israeli
helicopters over Western Beqaa, some 80 kilometers southeast of
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The anonymous security sources disclosed that the Israeli
forces were attempting to drop commandos to launch attacks on the
guerrilla targets, but the groundfire of the Lebanese army gunners
and the guerrillas in the area thwarted the operation.
</P>
<P>
However, the minor clash earlier this morning did not break a
rarely calm which has shrouded south Lebanon, the last active
battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict, since more than two
weeks except sporadic trades of fire.
</P>
<P>
In an ambush targeting a patrol of the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army (SLA) militia in the Israeli self-carved "security
zone" Tuesday, fighters of the Lebanese Shiite Hezbollah killed
one SLA militiaman and wounded five others.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state established the 1,100-square-kilometer buffer
zone in 1985 in a bid to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
