<HEADLINE> Michael Chang Set to Regain Salem Open Title in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- With the absence of world's
top-ranked Pete Sampras of the United States, his fellow
countryman Michael Chang poses as the hottest title contender at
the Salem Open tennis tournament which opened here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As top-seeded Sampras had earlier quit the annual Hong Kong
event due to a wrist injury suffered last month, Chang was lifted
by the organizers as top seed for the 328,000 U.S. dollar event.
</P>
<P>
Chang, a 27-year-old American-Chinese and two-time winner of
the Salem Open, is seeking a major title in Asia after a
disappointed 1996 season when every Asian title had eluded him.
</P>
<P>
According to the draw carried out here on Saturday, the
third-ranked Chang begins his assault on Monday to regain the
title which was taken from him at last year's event by Sampras.
</P>
<P>
Chang will take on and is expected to win over Hong Kong's
Melvin Tong in the men's singles main draw's first round.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion from the 1992 Games Marc Rosset of Switzerland
 will take on Nicolas Kiefer from Germany in the first round on
Monday. The second-seeded Rosset is ranked 16th in the world.
</P>
<P>
Australia's third seed Todd Woodbridge, now ranked 26th in the
world, will meet Doug Flach from the United States, also on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Other seeds of the nine-day event are Sweden's Thomas
Johansson, ranked 39th, Australia's Salem Open regular participant
Patrick Rafter, now ranked 43rd in the world, Czech Republic's
Martin Damm, who defeated Chang in the second round at last year's
Beijing Open, David Prinosil from Germany and another Czech Daniel
Vacek.  
</P>
