<HEADLINE> Rwandan Court Confirms First Death Penalty for Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A Rwandan higher court Friday
confirmed the first death penalty given to a former official
convicted of genocide in the 1994 massacre against Tutsis and
moderate Hutus, the Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Court of Appeal of Kigali rejected an appeal by Egide
Gatanazi, 43, who was convicted of murders, rapes and lootings by
the Tribunal of First Instance of Kibungo in southeast Rwanda on
January 3 in the country's first genocide trial.
</P>
<P>
The Court of Appeal will make a ruling on April 18 on the
appeal by Geogratias Bizimana, a 37-year-old male nurse, who was
convicted of genocide by the same court.
</P>
<P>
The two men pleaded not guilty during their trial which began
last December, two years and a half after Hutu extremists killed
at least 500,000 people from April to July 1994.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 people, most of them Hutus, are now in prison
waiting for trial on charges of genocide.
</P>
<P>
At least 16 other people have also been given death penalties
for genocide by lower courts of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
