<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Aging Scientists to Give Way to Younger Ones: New Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Academy of Science (CAS),
the country's top scientific body, announced here today that in
principle scientists over age of 65 will not be given jobs as
heads of the country's major scientific research projects.
</P>
<P>
The academy made the decision in an effort to promote the
country's outstanding young scientists to key research positions
at a faster pace.
</P>
<P>
There are 48,000 researchers and other technical professionals
working with CAS, 60 percent of whom are young scientists under
the age of 45, according to Prof. Lu Yongxiang, vice-president of
CAS.
</P>
<P>
"But only one fourth of these young scientists have the titles
of 'associate professor' or 'full professor'," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"On the other hand, about 3,000 research fellows and full
professors, accounting for three fourths of the academy's senior
scientists, will retire in the next three years," Lu told the
annual working meeting of CAS.
</P>
<P>
"As a rule, CAS has decided that at least half of the leaders
of the academy's major research projects during the period of the
Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000) must be under the age of
50, and senior scientists above the age of 65 will not be
appointed as leaders of research projects," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Now, only 19 percent of the leaders of the academy's major
research projects are under the age of 45. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
