<HEADLINE> Farmland Sinks in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A section of farmland recently
sank in Ruijin, east China's Jiangxi Province, but no deaths or
injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
The provincial authorities said that within 90 minutes, the 300
sq meter area of land, located beside a main road linking Ruijin
and Nanchang, sank six meters. A vapor could be seen rising from
the spot, observers said.
</P>
<P>
"An ox eating grass on the ridge suddenly let out a roar and
jumped up to the road, then the land began to sink," said local
farmers.
</P>
<P>
After a thorough investigation, the local department in charge
of earthquake work reported that the land was located on a bed of
limestone, and the sinking was a result of corrosion caused by
underground water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
