<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan FM on Ending Ethnic Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Lakshman Kadirgamar briefed editors of local newspapers on the
process that had led to the agreement between the People's
Alliance (PA) and the United National Party (UNP) on ending the
ethnic conflict, according to a news release from the ministry
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The release said the foreign minister Friday night told the
editors that there was no plan at this point for talks with the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
"The government had consistently expressed willingness to open
a dialogue with the LTTE, subject to conditions including a
substantial laying down of arms and an agreement to arrive at a
settlement within a stipulated time frame," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar also said the government was not contemplating
mediation or facilitation by any foreign government or third party
at this point.
</P>
<P>
He observed that he saw this agreement "as significant" and had
 described it "as a step on along road."
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the editors "to view this important step taken
constructively and to give this new approach a chance to work in
the national interest."
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga and opposition leader Ranil
Wickremesinghe Thursday agreed for the first time to cooperate on
their approach to ending the ethnic conflict which has killed
55,000 people.  
