<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Top Scientist Outlines Blueprint for Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS), the country's top scientific body, has decided to tackle
large-scale research projects related to the economy and the
market in the remaining years of this century.
</P>
<P>
This is one of four major tasks the staff of the academy must
complete by the turn of the century, CAS President Zhou Guangzhao
said at the organization's annual meeting which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the to-do list is creating a pool of CAS elites to
focus on the frontier sciences; training a new and competent
generation of scientists; and building CAS into an
internationally-advanced scientific research base that educates
high-level professionals and promotes the growth of China's
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that China's unique conditions, notably its
population, resources, and environment, mean that China has to
practice resource-conservation in regard to production and
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
"China must rely on quality rather than quantity in order to
seek further development," Zhou said. "China has to substitute
scarce resources with creativity and knowledge, and serve the
market with more science-intensive products."
</P>
<P>
"Scientific researchers, therefore, will have higher
requirements as well as more opportunities," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he expects Chinese scientists to climb to the pinnacle
of the sciences and develop high-tech products that can lead the
world market.
</P>
<P>
CAS will concentrate on making groundbreaking studies on
electronics and informatics, biotechnology, new materials and
applications, advanced manufacturing techniques, new energy and
environment technology, space technology, and oceanic technology,
Zhou said, as these fields are closely related to strategic needs
of the national economy and people's way of life.
</P>
<P>
Study results will be applied according to market demands, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that it is imperative for CAS to train qualified
people, as many of its senior researchers will retire in a few
years. He hoped that those who retire but are still in good health
will continue to help young people involved in the
sciences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
