<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- On the eve of the opening in Pretoria of the negotiations
with the Zairean government, the rebels of Laurent-Desire Kabila
Friday took Mbuji Mayi, the capital of the diamond-producing
province of eastern Kasai in central Zaire. Mbuji Mayi, which is
the objective of the rebels after their capture of Kisangani, fell
hours after Zairean government troops looted the town and fled
without a fight.
</P>
<P>
-- Thirty months after the American intervention which drove
General Cedras out and restored President Aristide, Haiti is
suffering from a slump and is threatened by a rampant anarchy. The
discontent of the Haitians will be shown through an expected weak
participation rate in the Senate election to be held on Sunday,
which is predicted at 10 percent at the most.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton has chosen New York banker Felix
Rohatyn as the new U.S. Ambassador to France, reported the Wall
Street Journal. Rohatyn, 68, general director of the bank of
investment of Lazard Brothers, is one of two candidates most
likely to succeed Ambassador Pamela Harriman, who died on February
5.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- By the year 2000, the earth will have 6.09 billion
inhabitants. After 2100, the world population will be stabilized
at 11 billion, said the French National Institute of Demographic
Studies.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 5 billion people will be living in developing countries,
against a little more than 1 billion in developed countries. Asia
will have 61 percent of the world population, while Europe will
have 11 percent. 
</P>
