<HEADLINE> S. Leone's President Denies Sankoh's Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Officials here have rejected
charges by disputed leader of the Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) Corporal Foday Sankoh that President Tejan Kabbah had
plotted his overthrow.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh made the charge in a BBC network Africa program on
Friday in which he claimed that the plan was ''hatched'' by the
Sierra Leone President.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Adviser on Peace Sheka Mansaray described
Sankoh's charges as ''Ludicrous and Baseless'', saying, ''the
Sierra Leone government would never undertake such venture.
</P>
<P>
Mansaray said the RUF members in the Commission for the
Consolidation of Peace (CCP) were only interested in advancing
peace after ''so much lives had been lost and massive destruction
done to their motherland''.
</P>
<P>
''There was no question of our urging them to overthrow Sankoh
or promises of ministerial posts and directors of parastatals,''
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Some senior RUF members toppled Sankoh in a coup and Sankoh
was arrested in Lagos, Nigeria for having brought with him arms
into the country.
</P>
<P>
Some field commanders of the RUF backed Sankoh and lured seven
senior RUF members into a trap in Nongowa in eastern Sierra Leone
last week and the two RUF representatives in the CCP, Fayia Musa
and Ibrahim Deen-Jalloh were seized among them.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh in his broadcast made no reference to the fate of
Sierra Leone's Ambassador to Guinea, Mohamed Diaby but diplomatic
sources here believe the envoy will be used as a ''bargaining
chip'' for the release of Sankoh from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
West African diplomats say the capture of Diaby, who was until
his diplomatic appointment six years ago was the Commander of the
Sierra Leone Navy, has earned the RUF ''a strong bargaining
power''.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Kabbah, speaking at a rally in Freetown
on Thursday, said, he ''is prepared to beg Nigeria to free Sankoh
in the interest of peace in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
