<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Exhibition on Port Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition entitled "the
Fragrant Harbor: An Overview of Its Maritime Trade and Port
Development" opened in Kowloon Park here today.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition features the development of the maritime trade
and port of Hong Kong from the Tang Dynasty (618-907) to the
present.
</P>
<P>
Through some 100 photos on display, visitors will be able
to see an interesting collection of historical evidence that
reveals the territory's early growth as a seaport.
</P>
<P>
Among them are an early sea chart, excavated fragments of an
ancient wooden ship and ceramics finds dating several centuries
ago.
</P>
<P>
There are also photos of early days tea label and shipping
schedules, as well as scenes of docks and local trading districts
of a bygone era.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Urban Council said that Tuen Mun was already
a port of Guangzhou as early as from the Tang Dynasty. By the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644), Hong Kong had probably become a stop on the "Maritime
Silk Road".
</P>
<P>
He said that it is evidenced by the artifacts unearthed from
Peony's Bay as recorded in the photos.
</P>
<P>
Some blue-and-white porcelains believed to be produced in
Jingdezhen in Jiangxi province and Martarban produced in
Southeast Asia were found.
</P>
<P>
There is also a section on the transformation in the modes of
sea transport that had since appeared in the territory's waters,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Visitors will see Hong Kong's progress of becoming an entrepot
and its eventual emergence as a thriving financial and commercial
center in the Asia-Pacific region, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
