<HEADLINE> Thai Prime Minister Back From China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Gen. Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh returned to Bangkok this afternoon after concluding a
four-day official visit to China.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held upon his arrival at the airport, he
recalled that during his visit, which began on Wednesday, he met
with Chinese President Jiang Zemin and held fruitful talks with
his Chinese counterpart Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
He also met with Vice Premier Zhu Rongji and Liu Huaqing, vice
chairman of the Central Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Thai prime minister witnessed the signing of six agreements
and memorandums of understanding -- on mutual visa exemption for
diplomats and officials, the maintaining of the Thai consulate in
Hong Kong after July 1 this year, cooperation in trade, economic
and investment, and in irrigation, agriculture and marine
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Charge d'Affaires ad interim Guan Mu and other senior
Chinese diplomats in the kingdom and senior Thai government
officials were at the airport to welcome the prime minister's
return.
</P>
<P>
China was the first non-ASEAN country which Chavalit has
visited since he took office as prime minister last December.
</P>
