<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Raises Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian oil authorities announced
that prices of all oil products, including super petrol and fuel
oil, rose by 25 percent throughout the country as from today.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the price
increase was announced in a statement by the Public Relations
Department of the Iranian Oil Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Iran raised the fuel prices by 50 percent last year and 100
percent the previous year. The move triggered some protests and
demonstrations from the local people, who complain about the
runaway inflation.
</P>
<P>
According to the Oil Ministry, the price of leaded and
non-leaded super petrol has been increased by 30 rials (0.001
U.S. dollars) per liter, bringing their price to 160 rials
(0.053 dollars) per liter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, price of super petrol rose to 220 rials (0.07
dollars), up by 40 rials (0.013 dollars) a liter, and gas oil
to 40 rials (0.013 dollars), up by 20 rials (0.006 dollar).
</P>
<P>
Under the Second Five-Year Development Plan (1995-1999),
prices of oil products will be increased slightly every year,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The price increases were planned at the beginning of the new
Iranian calendar year starting from March 21, but were
postponed to after the new year holidays.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices in the oil-rich Iran are still among the lowest in
the world. It costs about four U.S. dollars to fill a car with
super petrol.
</P>
<P>
But economic observers here have noted that the price hike
will boost the inflation rate. Official figures put the inflation
rate at 26 percent, but observers say that the inflation is about
60 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
