<HEADLINE> Turkey Plans to Provide Aid to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will to provide
50-million-dollar aid to Albania as it was racked by weeks of
violence, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a high-ranking government official, who
declined to be named, as saying that Turkey is "about to
complete studies on a 50-million-dollar donation to Albania, an
effort to help the country overcome its difficulties."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Onur Oymen traveled to
Albania last week to assess the situation in Albania where
violence erupted after the collapse of pyramid schemes in which
many citizens lost their life's savings.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Turkey was prepared to contribute troops to any
international effort for aid distribution in Albania and a
contingent of 500 Turkish troops are expected to be sent for
this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is concerned about the developments in Albania, which
it sees as a country with an important place in the Balkans and
whose stability is linked with that of the region.
</P>
<P>
Turkey fears that if the Albanian situation gets out of hand
it could spill over into Macedonia, where nearly half the
population is of Albanian origin.
</P>
<P>
Turkey signed a military cooperation agreement with Albania
in 1995 and the two countries have held several joint military
exercises under NATO's Partnership for Peace program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctor Succeeds in Duplicating Human Ear on Animal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese doctor has succeeded in
duplicating the human ear by conducting cell-reproduction
experiments on animals.
</P>
<P>
The research of plastic surgeon Cao Yilin, who works at the
Shanghai No. 9 People's Hospital, is said to offer bright
prospects for those whose organs have been damaged or lost.
</P>
<P>
Cao began his research 1993, based on his clinical experiences
in plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
To copy an organ, Cao takes cells from the organ to be
reproduced and cultivates them on a trestle-like apparatus made of
special material. He then transplants the cartilage derived from
the cells on a white mouse. A human ear appears on the animal in
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
"The technology is expected to be used on human bodies by the
end of the century, as the histological engineering develops," Cao
said. Based on the same principle, trachea, liver, joint, tendon,
skin and bones for human beings can all be reproduced by
collecting some active tissues of the ailing organs."
</P>
<P>
Dai Kerong, a renowned orthopedic surgeon in China, said that
histological engineering is different from cloning DNA, in that
the former reproduces cell tissues and can be widely used in
clinical practices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
