<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Value of Kuwait Government Holdings Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The value of Kuwaiti
government holdings has more than doubled since 1994 when the
government started selling shares in its companies in the
process of privatization.
</P>
<P>
Ali Rashaid, Director of Kuwait Investment Authority (KIA), the
country's only managing body of government assets, told local
English daily Arab Times in an exclusive interview published
today that "at the start of the privatization program, KIA's
local holdings were worth around 850 million Kuwait Dinars (2.8
billion U.S. dollars)."
</P>
<P>
He said that even after the sale of 20 companies, the
value of the remaining holdings is now around one billion dinars
(3.3 billion U.S. dollars)."
</P>
<P>
Selling of shares in the 20 companies had generated 750
million dinars (2.475 billion U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rashaid said that the Kuwait stock exchange market
grew by 58 percent since the beginning of 1996, reflecting more
confidence and better results for the listed companies.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Kuwaiti government's policy is to privatize
its holdings in local firms, including listed and unlisted
companies.
</P>
<P>
This policy is aimed at attracting more private capital to
the local stock exchange while increasing the role of the
private sector, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
