<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Invests 240 Million Dollars for Ambitious Science Projects (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China disclosed a number of
ambitious scientific projects here today, which include building
the world's most advanced telescope that will allow scientists to
carry out surveys of at least 100 million galaxies.
</P>
<P>
"The schemes form part of a massive two billion yuan (241
million US dollars) state investment plan for four ambitious
science projects in the remaining years of this century," said
Professor Lu Yongxiang, vice-president of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences(CAS).
</P>
<P>
The package includes the construction of an advanced sky
survey telescope, a national synchronous radiation laboratory, a
earth crust movement monitoring network and an advanced light
source that is at lease 100 million times brighter than X-ray
light.
</P>
<P>
China will build a sky survey telescope, which is the most
advanced in the world, at Xinglong hill in Yanshan Mountains of
north China.
</P>
<P>
"The large area, multi-object spectrum telescope, with a
calibre of four meters and a length of 40 meters, can observe at
least 100 million galaxies, which will open up a brand-new area
for astronomy during the trans-century period," Professor Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, CAS will build eight more light beams and eight
laboratories for the Hefei-based National Synchronous Radiation
Laboratory in eastern China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
"The completion of this synchronous radiation device will land
China in the front in the coming decades," Lu noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, CAS and Shanghai municipal government will jointly
build a new-generation synchrotron light source in China's largest
city of Shanghai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
