<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Reforms Help Manila Attract More Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investments in the
Philippines reached 18.7 billion U.S. dollars last year, an
increase of 22.2 percent over the previous year, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that foreign investments in the country will
soar to 20 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Local economists have attributed the significant increase in
the foreign investments to a succession of economic reforms and
vigorous measures the government had undertaken to attract foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1980s, foreign investments in the Philippines were
less dynamic than in other Asian economies because of chronic
political instability and structural economic problems such as
strong protection of domestic industries through regulation,
fragile financial system, stagnant exports and huge trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
After taking office in 1992, President Fidel Ramos first
stabilized the political situation and strengthened his power base
by reconciling with coupists, holding peace talks with rebel
groups and forging an alliance with the largest opposition party
in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Then, the government passed the Foreign Investment Act of 1991,
which in principle removed all restrictions on foreign capital
participation.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by the liberalization of foreign exchange
transactions in 1992 and the extension of the land leasing period
from 50 to 75 years for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the deregulation of the telecommunications and the
power industries brought a large amount of foreign investments
into the country.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the financial system was reformed through a
series of measures including the reorganization of the Central
Bank which was heavily in debt, the merger of two stock exchanges
into the Philippine Stock Exchange and the decision to allow 10
foreign banks to enter the local market for the first time in half
a century.
</P>
<P>
To attract more foreign investments, the government also put
the creation of economic zones as its top priority, introducing a
number of favorable incentives for foreign enterprises entering
these zones.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine Economic Zone Authority, there are
now 54 economic zones across the country with some 550 foreign
companies located inside.
</P>
<P>
Last year, foreign firms invested at least 2.4 billion dollars
into these zones. And for the first two months this year, the
figure has reached 1.06 billion dollars, up by 530 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The effective efforts of the government have resulted in the
inflow of huge foreign investments and the fast growth of the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The economy, which jumped from zero growth in 1991 to 6.8
percent increase in 1996, will also grow by 7-8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
For the remarkable growth of economy, the country has been
cited as a "Tiger Economy" by some international companies.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the country has broad prospects for attracting
more foreign capital. Its labor remains cheaper and well-educated;
It is liberalizing more industries; The southern Philippines is
opening up more investment opportunities after the government and
the largest rebel group ended a 24-year-old war there last year.
</P>
<P>
However, some problems will also hinder the growth of the
country's foreign investments. These stumbling blocks include the
serious waves of kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
According to local press, 241 people were taken hostage last
year in the country. For the first three months this year, 54
kidnapping cases have occurred with kidnappers demanding at least
20 million dollars as ransom.
</P>
<P>
To ensure personal security, many foreign investors have to
hire security guards to protect themselves or their properties.
</P>
<P>
Some of the country's major investment partners in Asia and
Europe have also expressed their concern over the Philippines'
investment policies after the Supreme Court revoked the winning
bid of a Malaysian conglomerate for a controlling stake in the
historic Manila Hotel and rewarded it to a Filipino firm in
February.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
