<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week mixed.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market this week, trading was range-bound
and there was relatively less commitment from players who were
taking a wait- and-see approach while closely monitoring the
production data for March.
</P>
<P>
Against the previous close, April-South was offered unchanged
at 1,290 ringgit (about 516 U.S. dollars) a ton.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said strong leads expected on the futures market and
the possible emergence of fresh market-moving news should provide
a positive impact for the palm oil cash market to find better
ground next week.
</P>
<P>
However, with the uncertainties on the market's immediate
trend, any further consolidation would be based on technical
factors, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) was in range bound trading
this week with its price settling the week unchanged at 14.29
ringgit (about 5.716 dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover dropped to 370 tons from 404 tons last
week with European, Japanese and local buyers being the main
volume contributors on the market.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM is expected to be volatile next week with its price
likely to hover between 14.20 ringgit (about 5.68 dollars) and
14.35 ringgit (about 5.74 dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM is also anticipated to experience mild profit taking
at the start of next week, following the metal's continued easier
undertone on the London Metal Exchange (LME).
</P>
<P>
Tin, which is traded in US dollars on the LME, found good
support locally as the metal is considered to be cheaper here in
line with the expected weaker ringgit next week, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Malaysian rubber market closed the week
lower with sluggish trading as overseas buyers retreated to the
sidelines waiting for prices to ease further.
</P>
<P>
The May RSS 1 closed the week four sen lower to 294.50 sen
(about 117.8 U.S. cents) per kg, while the SMR 20 dropped seven
sen to 278.50 sen (about 111.4 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for April 3 stood at 225.36
Malaysian/Singapore cents (sen) from 228.38 cents (sen) on March
26.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average was at 226.94 cents per kg from
229.06 cents per kg.
</P>
<P>
The rubber market is expected to be mixed next week in
continued dull trading as most buyers, discouraged by the existing
"unaffordable" NR prices, are waiting for prices to ease to a more
attractive level, traders said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
