<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila-MILF Peace Talks Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have rescheduled their talks
slated for next week in order to conduct investigations into last
month's fighting in Buldon, Mindanao, a government negotiator said
today.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview in Cotabato city, Mindanao, Fortunato
Abat, chief government negotiator said that the two sides agreed
Friday to reschedule talks to "give way for the government-MILF
created Interim Ceasefire Monitoring Committee (ICMC) to conduct
investigations on the Buldon issue."
</P>
<P>
On March 16, government troops and MILF rebels exchanged mortar
fires in Buldon, killing 11 civilians and displacing hundreds of
families in the region. The government and the MILF accused each
other of violating an interim ceasefire in the area.
</P>
<P>
Abat said that during his talks with a rebel leader Friday, the
MILF threatened to postpone future peace negotiations with the
government unless the Buldon issue will be resolved.
</P>
<P>
"The ICMC will start their probe on April 7 and will give an
official report on April 9. It (will be) too close for the talks
slated for April 9-10," Abat said.
</P>
<P>
Abat said that the third government-MILF technical committee
meeting was tentatively rescheduled on April 22-25 to "give an
allowance for the MILF's request."
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-strong MILF has become the country's major rebel
group after the government and the Moro National Liberation Front
signed a pact on peace in Mindanao last September. The MILF
rejected the peace pact and is continuing its fighting for an
independent state in Mindanao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
