<HEADLINE> Indian PM Seeks Legal Opinion on Dissolution of House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- As India's Congress party
hardened its stance to press for his resignation, Prime Minister
H.D. Deve Gowda on Friday sought legal opinion to recommending
dissolution of the Lok Sabha (the lower house of parliament) and
holding of fresh elections, The Hindustan Times said today.
</P>
<P>
Official sources, while confirming that a request to the effect
had gone from the Prime Minister's Office (PMO) to the Law
Ministry, declined to go into details.
</P>
<P>
As informal parleys between leaders of the ruling United Front
and the Congress party reportedly suffered a setback on Friday,
Deve Gowda's move gave rise to speculation that he might opt for
recommending dissolution instead of facing the Lok Sabha on April
11 for a confidence motion as requested by the president.
</P>
<P>
The current political crisis arose out of the Congress party's
withdrawal of support to the 14-party United Front government last
Sunday, a move which reduced the government to a minority.
</P>
