<HEADLINE> Indian Airlines Asked to Shed Foreign Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government on Friday
directed Jet Airways, an Indian domestic air carrier, to shed its
40 percent foreign equity stake within six months, The Financial
Express reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government gave the direction following the announcement of
new investment norms for entry of foreign airlines into the
domestic aviation sector earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Under the new investment norms, foreign airlines are barred
from holding equity stake in India's domestic aviation sector.
</P>
<P>
"Domestic air carriers in which foreign airlines hold equity
directly or indirectly have been given six months time to
disinvest," Indian Civil Aviation Minister C.M. Ibrahim told a
press conference here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
While 60 percent of equity holding in Jet Airways is held by a
non-resident Indian, the remaining 40 percent stake is held
equally by Gulf and Kuwait Airways.  
</P>
</TEXT>
