<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) market fell sharply this week with
over-reaction by players to the National Bank's announcement on
the lending curbs to reduce property.
</P>
<P>
Although most analysts feel the market's sharp fall this week
is not attributable to the central bank ruling, which was
announced last Friday, confidence seems to have drained out of the
market ever since.
</P>
<P>
"The market should by now fully digest to the new ruling. We
feel that the market actually is now in its consolidation phase...
the central bank's action should not warrant the current bearish
sentiment. It is just a matter of timing," they said.
</P>
<P>
They also viewed that there was unlikely to be any rebound at
this point of time as most retail investors were selling
aggressively in order to cut further losses.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE Composite Index closed at 1,136.78 points, the lowest
so far this year, down 80.86 points from the previous close of
1,217.64.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index declined 28.06 points to 329.29 from 357.35, the
Industrial Index plunged 122.66 points to 2,143.10 from 2,265.76
and the Second Board Index fell to 607.82 from 673.46.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover for the week was 1.845 billion shares worth
12.583 billion ringgit (about 5.0332 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mainboard turnover totaled 1.580 billion shares worth 9.517
billion ringgit (about 3.8068 billion dollars), up slightly from
an estimated 1.435 billion shares worth 8.591 billion ringgit
(about 3.4364 billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Second board turnover totaled 265.061 million shares worth
3.066 billion ringgit (about 1.2264 billion dollars) compared with
330.499 million shares worth 3.980 billion ringgit (about 1.592
billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off market deals declined to 239.436 million shares worth 1.683
billion ringgit (about 673.2 million dollars) from 331.265 million
shares worth 2.135 billion ringgit (about 854 million dollars)
last week.
</P>
<P>
Aokam Perdana was the week's most active counter with 120.227
million shares or 6.51 percent of the total shares traded. It
closed at 3.74 ringgit, down 2.11 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Among other active counters this week were Tekala Corporation
down 1.45 ringgit to 6.95 ringgit on a turnover of 57.240 million
shares, Sime Darby 55 sen lower to 8.50 ringgit with 44.042
million shares traded, Suria Capital lowered by 51 sen to 2.83
ringgit with 28.477 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 124.530
million shares traded, industrial products 388.434 million shares,
construction 111.233 million shares, trading/services 208.113
million shares, and infrastructure 2.565 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Investors are expected to adopt a cautious stance on the KLSE
next week as potential for the market to further decline is
evident before any rebound takes place, the analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
