<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Booms in Chittagong Export Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) --- Bangladesh has seen a boom of
foreign investments in its first operational export processing
zone based in the southeastern port city of Chittagong following a
lull in political unrest.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, in the first six months of the
current fiscal year beginning from last July, the Chittagong
Export Procession Zone (CEPZ) drew a foreign investment of 11
million U.S. dollars, an increase of 32 percent compared with that
of the corresponding period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Presently investment surged to 177 million U.S. dollars in the
CEPZ which was commissioned in the year 1983 with an investment
below one million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Officials said investments in the CEPZ may go up by another 30
million dollars in the next six months with the commissioning of
13 more industries.
</P>
<P>
The CEPZ, set up over 450 acres of land near Bangladesh's
largest seaport, has so far housed 71 operational industries.
</P>
<P>
South Korea topped the list with 17 industries while Japan
secured the second position with 12 industries, official reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The entrepreneurs of 13 industries now under implementation
stage at CEPZ are from Spain, the United States, the United
Kingdom, Hong Kong, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CEPZ exported finished goods worth 159 million
dollars from July to December of the current fiscal years as
against 124 million dollars during the same period in the last
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The exported goods include electronics, sports shoes, readymade
garments, golf equipment, cap and camera lens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
