<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Hold Talks with India on Ganges Water Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A two-member Indian delegation is
due here today to hold talks with the Bangladeshi side on the
Ganges Water Sharing Treaty, which has remained practically
inoperative since March this year, according to officials from the
Water Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Indian side earlier had decided to hold the Joint River
Commission (JRC) meeting but the meeting was abandoned due to the
internal political situation in India. Instead the India now
decided to hold the official level talks.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh officials said that as per the agreement, the Indian
side is supposed to regulate the withdrawal of water at the
upstream of Farakka Barrage, dozens of miles north of the
Bangladeshi border.
</P>
<P>
The Indian authorities, however, did not take any step in this
regard to ensure the availability of water at the Farakka point,
the officials complained, adding that the meeting would take stock
of the Indian initiatives of implementing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indian side has reportedly informed Bangladesh
that the Ganges water flow slowed down as the ice in the Himalayas
where the Ganges originates was not melting enough to raise the
level.
</P>
<P>
Under the 30-year Ganges Water Treaty signed in December 1996,
if the water flow at the Farakka Barrage falls below 70,000 cusecs
(cubic feet per second), the two countries should split the water
evenly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
