<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Access to Refugees in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council today called on all parties in Zaire, particularly the
rebels led by Laurent Kabila, to allow aid agencies access to
thousands of stranded refugees, many of whome are dying of
malnutrition and disease.
</P>
<P>
Council President Antonio Monteiro of Portugal said that the
Security Council reiterated its deep concern over the alarming
situation of refugees and displaced persons in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"They (refugees) need help and they need it now," he told
reporters after a meeting of the council.
</P>
<P>
The council urges the parties, particularly Kabila's rebel
Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire
(ADFL), to ensure safe access of humanitarian aid to, and the
safety of, all refugees, displaced persons and other affected
civilian inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council urged the ADFL to cooperate fully with the
United Nations in the implementation of the repatriation plan of
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). It also
called on the government of Rwanda to help the implementation of
this plan.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Zaire has been plagued by civil war over the past six
months. The fighting between the government and the ADFL has
driven countless Rwandan refugees and local people into the
country's interior.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people, mostly women and children, have already
died or are dying of exhaustion, hunger and disease.
</P>
<P>
U.N. humanitarian aid agencies have tried to assist more than
100,000 refugees who have re-emerged from the forest over the past
week. There are 200,000 more displaced persons who are still
beyond reach.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR, while trying to stabilize the refugees around Kisangani
and Ubandu in eastern Zaire, plans to repatriate Rwandan refugees
who fled their country after the conflict between Hutu and Tutsi
broke out in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
