<HEADLINE> German President Leaves for Japan after Malaysia Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 5 (Xinhua) -- German President Roman Herzog
left Kuching, East Malaysia, for Tokyo today after ending his
six-day official visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In Kuching, capital of Sarawak state in East Malaysia, the last
leg of his visit to the country, Herzog, who turns 63 today, was
given a surprise birthday party before being accorded a warm and
traditional send-off, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
He flew to Kuching Friday from Kuala Lumpur where he had an
audience with Malaysian King Tuanku Ja'afar and met Malaysian
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
During the visit in Malaysia, the German president assured
continued German investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade between Germany and Malaysia amounted to
12.6 billion ringgit (about 5.04 billion U.S. dollars) each year
and direct investment by German companies operating in Malaysia
amounted to 5.6 billion ringgit (about 2.24 billion dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
