<HEADLINE> Nepali King Issues Ordinance to Amend Local Body Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 5 (Xinhua) -- King of Nepal Birendra has
issued an ordinance to amend some of the country's acts concerning
local administration bodies and their elections.
</P>
<P>
According to a press statement by the Cabinet Secretariat on
Friday evening, the king made the issue after receiving a
submission from the government of Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur
Chand seeking the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement did not specify what amendments will be
made to the existing acts on the local bodies and elections under
the king's ordinance.
</P>
<P>
The Chand government, which came to power last month, had
pledged to empower local administration bodies and local people
through ordinance as a bill on decentralization could not be
passed in the parliament session concluding recently.
</P>
<P>
The one-month Winter session of parliament, which witnessed the
fall of the former government under Sher Bahadur Deuba due to its
losing of confidence vote and the formation of Chand's government,
failed to discuss any important bill as the new government claimed
it had no adequate time to present the bills.
</P>
<P>
Opposition lawmakers had demanded the government to hold the
upcoming local elections only after the decentralization bill,
expected to give more autonomous rights to local bodies, is
approved by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The local elections, already scheduled to be held by the end of
June, will elect chief officers and representatives for local
administration bodies on village, municipality and district levels
throughout the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
