<HEADLINE> No Accused Arrested in Stock Scandal in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- None of the remaining 28 people,
accused of manipulating Bangladesh's capital market during a bull
run last year, could be arrested till today, according to the
police sources.
</P>
<P>
The Security and Exchange Commission (sec) had charged 32 people
on Wednesday on the basis of a report by an independent committee
which probed the biggest ever "white collar crime" in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
But four of the accused on Thursday obtained anticipatory bail
till Sunday from the high court division of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Others are expected to make a move to obtain bail together on
Sunday to avoid being arrested, sources in the stock market said.
</P>
<P>
Police said that they have continued their search for the
accused since a magistrate issued warrants of arrest against them
following the SEC complaints filed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But they were not available in their respective addresses, said
the police sources.
</P>
<P>
The accused are some leading businessmen in Bangladesh,
including the Chairman of Dhaka Stock Exchange Imtiyaz Hossain and
some other members of the largest bourse of Bangladesh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
