<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Finance Ministers' Meeting Opens in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CEBU, The Philippines, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The fourth Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) finance ministers' meeting
opened here today to seek ways to stimulate the private sector's
participation in infrastructure development in the region.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Philippine President Fidel Ramos said it
is a formidable task for the 18 APEC member economies to meet huge
financial requirements of infrastructure development which is key
to sustainable economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the financial needs of infrastructure development
would reach some 1.5 trillion U.S. dollars over the next decade
which is hard for the governments to meet.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the fourth APEC leaders meeting in Subic,
the northern Philippines, last November called on the finance
ministers to pursue effective measures to establish efficient
financial and capital markets and encourage the private sector to
participate in infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the finance ministers will try to
reach agreement on the facilitation of the private sector's
participation in infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss measures to accelerate the development
of domestic financial and capital markets and maintain stable and
free flows of capital in the region.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the finance ministers' meeting are the
presidents of the International Monetary Fund and the Asia
Development Bank, and representatives from the APEC Business
Advisory Council (ABAC) and the Pacific Economic Cooperation
Council (PECC).
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the ABAC and the PECC to be invited
to a dialogue with the finance ministers. The PECC is currently
the only private-sector-associated organization enjoying observer
status at APEC ministerial and senior officials meetings.
</P>
<P>
Parallel to the finance ministers' meeting, the APEC Financiers
Group, an advisory group composed of leading financiers from the
APEC member economies, is also meeting in Cebu, capital of Cebu
province in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among the Asia-Pacific economies. It groups
Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong, Indonesia,
Japan, The Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua
New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore, Chinese Taipei, Thailand
and the United States.  
</P>
