<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian GDP Forecasts for 1997 Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- One of Austria's top economic
bodies raised its growth estimate for Austria's gross domestic
product (GDP) this year from 1.0 percent to 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Helmut Kramer, president of the Austrian Institute for Economic
Research (AIER), and Bernhard Feladerer, president of the Senior
AIER published their forecasts at a joint press conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
Having forecast last December a 1.0 percent increase in the GDP
in 1997, Kramer raised his forecast to 1.2 percent today.
</P>
<P>
Showing more optimism than Kramer, Feladerer repeated
his forecast of 1.5 percent growth made last December.
</P>
<P>
Kramer and Feladerer believed that the policies adopted by the
government in controlling the budget would not lead to a negative
impact on economic development.
</P>
<P>
On international trade, they forecast that exports would rise
faster than imports. Both expected a 6.6 percent increase in
exports in 1997 and 7.8 percent in 1998. Imports are expected to
grow 3.6 percent in 1997 and 5.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
But they disagreed on unemployment and inflation control.
</P>
<P>
Kramer predicted that the unemployment rate in 1997 be the same
as last year' 7 percent, while Feladerer forecast unemployment
at 7.4 percent in 1997 and 7.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
On inflation, Kramer believed the rate would drop from 1.9
percent this year to 1.6 percent in 1988, while Feladerer forecast
a higher rate of 2 or 2.1 percent in the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
