<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks' Bad Loans to Peak in 1998: Specialist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's banking crisis is
likely to be more serious and prolonged than authorities expect,
according to an expert with the International Credit Rating Agency
Standard and Poor's.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans are likely to be much worse than forecast
by the Bank of Thailand, the Bangkok Post today quoted Peter
Sikora, a banking specialist with the Standard and Poor's
Melbourne office, as saying in a teleconference call.
</P>
<P>
Sikora predicted that non-performing loan levels would peak
next year at 12-15 percent of the total loans for commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
This could be even higher for finance and securities firms,
given their heavier involvement in speculative operations such as
securities margin and vehicle hire-purchase loans.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand last reported bank non-performing loans at
7.7 percent of the total, as of June 1996, with private analysts
believing the level went well into the double digits by the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, however, Cem Karacadag, a director of the
Standard and Poor's New York office, said Thailand's financial
position is more than capable of weathering the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The fundamental credit strengths and weaknesses of
Thailand simply have not changed. And that is the basis for our
stable outlook on both the long-term 'a' foreign currency and the
long-term 'AA' local currency ratings for the kingdom."
</P>
<P>
He added that the Thai government's strong financial position,
spurred by nine years of fiscal surpluses, had given policy makers
ample space and flexibility in responding to shocks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
