<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 163 Journalists Slain in L. America Over Last Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 163 journalists
were assassinated in Latin America over the last eight and a half
years, the Interamerican Press Association (SIP) said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Colombia was the most dangerous country for journalists, with
67 members of the press assassinated there, the SIP report said.
</P>
<P>
Mexico and Peru shared second place with 18 journalists
assasinated in each country, followed by El Salvador with 16,
Guatemala with 15 and Brazil with 13.
</P>
<P>
In Venezuela, Chile, Ecuador, Paraguay and Argentina fewer than
five journalists were killed in each country.
</P>
<P>
The death toll for most Latin American countries is much higher
than in North America and Haiti. Seven journalists were murdered
in the United States, five in Haiti and one in Canada.
</P>
<P>
There have been no assassinations of journalists in Panama for
several years, although cases of intimidation had been reported,
the SIP said.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Trotti, director of the SIP, told the First Latin
American Journalism Congress on Thursday that only one person has
been convicted so far for masterminding an assassination but
several of those who carried out the murders have been jailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
