<HEADLINE> Acid Rain Area Highlights Efforts to Combat Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South China's Liuzhou City reduced
the discharge by 13,000 tons of sulphur dioxide and 2,300 tons of
smoke and dust last year, according to the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
The city, an industrial powerhouse of the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, is one of the heavy acid rain areas in China,
and its 800,000 residents suffered a lot.
</P>
<P>
The Liuzhou City Government has resolved to combat the air
pollution since early last year. Forty measures have been taken,
and it was listed as the city's priority in 1996 to cut the
sulphur dioxide emissions by 10,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly 60 major polluters have promised to improve within a
specified time limit," said an official with the city
environmental protection department, adding that another 24
small-sized factories or workshops have been shut down.
</P>
<P>
The city prohibited the sale and use of the raw coal with
sulphur content above one percent, and the boilers in the central
city have been forced to be equipped with desulphurization
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city spent some a total of 18.5
million yuan (2.23 million US dollars) in combating air pollution
last year, and 31 key pollution control projects were completed.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
