<HEADLINE> Thailand, Laos Sign Transportation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Laos have signed a
transportation agreement, paving the way for the two countries to
be linked by a railway which will run over the border bridge
across the Mekong river, according to a report from Vientiane.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed on Friday in Vientiane, capital of
Laos, by Thai Minister of Transportation Suwat Liptapallop and his
Lao counterpart Phao Bounnaphon.
</P>
<P>
The agreement defines the border at the bridge site, clearing
the last legal obstacles to the construction of a rail link over
the Friendship Bridge.
</P>
<P>
The midway of the bridge is not directly above the deepest
waterway in the river, causing legal, management and maintenance
problems.
</P>
<P>
The Thai side will complete in September a section (about 20
kilometers) of the railway from Nong Khai to the middle of the
bridge, while the Lao side will build a 14-km track linking the
bridge with Vientiane.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund will provide Laos
with a loan amounting to 50 percent of the construction cost on
the Lao side.  
</P>
</TEXT>
