<HEADLINE> Massive Poverty Reduction Effort In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The successful completion of a
World-Bank poverty reduction project in the Tarim Basin of
northwestern Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region will mark the start
of a second-phase project, with a World Bank loan of 150 million
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The new project is expected to benefit more than five million
people in the basin, helping some of them become better off while
protecting their environment.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase project, which has a total investment of 1.65
billion yuan, including 125 million US dollars in World Bank
loans, has improved irrigation conditions greatly in the area and
lifted 2.2 million local people out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Over the past four years, the project helped open up 80,000
hectares of uncultivated land, improve 120,000 hectares of
low-yield farmland, and build infrastructure for water
conservation and husbandry.
</P>
<P>
An official from a World Bank Inspection Group that visited the
area several days ago said, "China is the most successful country
in carrying out World Bank-funded project, and the World Bank is
especially confident in Xinjiang, since agricultural development
in the area holds even greater potential than coastal regions."
</P>
</TEXT>
