<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Refined Oil Exports Jump in January, February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's refined oil exports in
the first two months this year posted 6.51 million barrels,
soaring up 545 percent compared with the same period of last year,
according to officials statistics.
</P>
<P>
The largest increase was seen in gasoline exports, which
skyrocketed 1,014 percent to 2.04 million barrels in January and
February this year, according to data from the Petroleum Institute
of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports of diesel oil in the period totaled 1.46
million barrels, an increase of 973.9 percent, which mostly were
exported to neighboring countries like Laos.
</P>
<P>
The Thai fuel oil exports rose 136 percent to 1.01 million
barrels in the period.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's exports of indigenous condensate were
914,500 barrels in the period, dropping 43.8 percent from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the sharp rise in refined oil exports in
January and February generally came as a result of the slowdown in
refined oil consumption in the country and oversupplies of local
refined oil products.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's refined oil consumption in the first two months of
the year grew up only 2 percent over the same period last year to
an average of 732,540 barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
The slowdown mainly stemmed from a significant drop in the use
of fuel oil, which is being replaced by indigenous natural gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
