<HEADLINE> China, Czech Republic Agree to Enhance Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Czech leaders today met and
exchanged views with visiting Chinese Vice Premier Wu Bangguo on
strengthening bilateral relations and other issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to take effective measures to push forward
economic and trade cooperation by increasing mutual understanding
and cultural, educational and scientific and technological
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
While meeting Wu, who arrived here Friday, Prime Minister Josef
Lux spoke highly of China's foreign policy based on mutual
respect, equality and mutual benefit, and non-interference in each
other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Both the Czech Republic and China are willing to develop their
friendly cooperation ties and Wu's visit will further develop
Czech-Sino relations, Lux said.
</P>
<P>
Milos Zeman, chairman of the Chamber of Deputies (lower house),
said exchange visits by the two nations' leaders will increase
mutual understanding and deepen friendship between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Czech Vice Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Josef Zielenice
said his country values its friendship with China by sticking to
the One-China policy and will not establish official links with
ChineseTaiwan.
</P>
<P>
Economic and trade ties, a major basis for Czech-Sino
relations, have developed smoothly over the last few years and
should continue to improve, Zielenice said.
</P>
<P>
Wu said China attaches great importance to developing its
relations with the Czech Republic as the two nations share the
same or similar views on many important issues.
</P>
<P>
There are no fundamental conflicting issues and problems left
over by history between China and the Czech Republic, so
furthering friendly cooperation is in the interests of the two
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
China, respecting the development path selected by the Czech
people themselves and the internal and external policies of the
Czech government, is ready to cooperate with Czech Republic in
dealing with international issues, the Chinese vice premier said.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic is the third leg of Wu's five-nation
European tour, which has taken him to Ukraine and Belarus and will
take him to Finland and Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
