<HEADLINE> Rehabilitation Program Benefits Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China is making marked progress in
its endeavors to help its 60 million disabled people, according
to a new official report.
</P>
<P>
This is shown in the growing number of people with physical
disabilities who have been benefited from a national
rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
Launched in 1988, the rehabilitation program has so far treated
2.32 million people who suffer from cataracts, polio or deafness
and changed their life for the better as a result, said a
spokesman of the China Disabled Persons' Federation yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The figure could be much bigger, if people with mental
disorders who have received community-based services in 235 cities
and other services, were included, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The federation, set up in 1988 to promote the rights and
interests of handicapped people, said in a report that in 1996:
</P>
<P>
-- 257,170 cataract suffers regained their sight;
</P>
<P>
-- 51,365 polio victims or those suffering spinal or joint
problems were operated on successfully;
</P>
<P>
-- 13,420 deaf children participated in hearing and speech
programs;
</P>
<P>
-- More than 24 million newly married and pregnant women and
babies took liquid iodine as a way to prevent mental diseases.
</P>
<P>
These achievements went far beyond the government's original
plan for the year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, most Chinese health departments and medical services
have included rehabilitation of people with disabilities in their
daily agenda.
</P>
<P>
Now the national rehabilitation program is switching its
priorities from medical care to later-stage rehabilitation
training and community rehabilitation services.
</P>
<P>
A total 873 offices have been established at the provincial,
city and county levels to provide guidance for local
rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
The federations has drafted two sets of requirements for
systematic training of mentally retarded children and those with
limb defects.
</P>
<P>
Experts are compiling teaching materials to help standardize
rehabilitation training.  
</P>
</TEXT>
