<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multinational Force Set to go to Albania From April 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The multinational protection force
set up to protect aid supplies to strife-torn Albania will be
deployed in the week starting April 14, the Italian Foreign
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting of representatives from the
eight countries which have either pledged to contribute forces or
are considering participation.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the force will coincide with the arrival of
humanitarian aid to the Balkan nation which has been in the grip
of violence and unrest for the last two months.
</P>
<P>
The main task of the protection force is to help implement
emergency relief operations. Italy is expected to send between
2,000 and 2,500 troops, France 1,000, Greece 700, Turkey 500,
Romania 400 and Spain 300. Austria and Denmark said they are still
considering participation.
</P>
<P>
The force is expected to secure key ports and transport routes
to protect the delivery of European humanitarian aid from armed
gunmen in the country.
</P>
<P>
Troops will be stationed in the southern ports of Vlore and
Durres and at Tirana airport so that food can be imported will
protect aid convoys inside the country.
</P>
<P>
The Rome-based World Food Program (WFP) said today it would be
sending an initial consignment of 420 tonnes of flour, beans and
oil to the Albanian port of Durres on April 9, from where it will
be sent on by truck to the main towns and cities of Tirana,
Kurtes, Peshkopia, Elbasan and Shkoder.
</P>
<P>
WFP Executive Director Catherine Bertini said,"The present food
situation in Albania has been made worse by the closing of
borders, which made imports impossible. Emergency assistance is
credible."
</P>
<P>
However, a military commentator from the London-based
Institute for Strategic Studies, Colonel Terence Taylor, cast
doubt on the wisdom of military intervention in the Balkan
country, saying that the Albanian solution was so confused that a
military mission did not appear credible.
</P>
<P>
"It is easy to talk about protecting humanitarian aid supplies,
but what happens if someone attacks a Red Cross vehicle, or a
military patrol?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Albania descended into chaos in early March when protests
triggered by the collapse of shaky investment schemes mushroomed
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people lost their life savings in the collapse and
blamed President Sali Berisha. The protests turned violent after
armed rebels looted army depots and took over several towns in the
south.
</P>
<P>
More than 13,000 refugees fled the country in March and the
Albanian government has called for international aid and military
intervention to help the new government of national reconciliation
restore order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steps Taken To Protect Yangtze River Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Effective measures are being taken
to prevent any further disruption of ship traffic on the Yangtze
River during construction of the Three Gorges Dam Project and
after it is completed, officials said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Navigation and project construction authorities gave the
assurances after a blockage at the adjacent Gezhouba Dam late last
month that delayed hundreds of vessels for some two weeks.
</P>
<P>
As of March 29, all the ships jammed at Lock II of the water
control and power project at Yichang in Central China's Hubei
Province had passed through the dam, according to today's "China
Daily". The ships had been waiting since March 11.
</P>
<P>
"We believe similar problems are unlikely to happen at the
ongoing Three Gorges Project, which is to dam the river this
November, and we are making greater efforts to guarantee that,"
said Liang Yingzhan, director of the Office for Three Gorges Dam
Navigation under the Ministry of Communications in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Liang described the latest Gezhouba disruption, which blocked
more than 600 vessels, as "accidental," because it was a result of
the urgent preparations of the dam's Lock II, and the
once-every-six-years major maintenance work of Lock III, as well
as the inadequate handling capacity of Lock I.
</P>
<P>
"It is very rare that two of the three locks of the dam are out
of order at the same time...but the accident certainly needs to be
taken seriously, especially as traffic flow increases in the
future," Liang said.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Wuhan-based Yangtze River Navigation
Administration told China Daily that the disruption was one of
several similar incidents that had occurred at the dam since it
opened in 1981.
</P>
<P>
During the traffic jam, Wuhan sources said, measures were taken
by local authorities to guarantee navigational safety.
</P>
<P>
Priority was given to free blocked passenger ships and freight
vessels carrying cargo for the Three Gorges Dam Project, China's
largest water control and power project, they said.
</P>
<P>
Tang Jie, an official with the Yichang-based Three Gorges Dam
Project Development and Construction Corp, said his company gave
close attention to the blockage at Gezhouba Dam.
</P>
<P>
"We have been working with related departments and the Ministry
of Communications to guarantee shipping and navigation on the
Yangtze River," Tang said during a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
From this coming November to 2003, ships will pass the site of
the dam through a 350-meter-wide channel. A temporary lock will
also open to pass ships through when the river's water flow
exceeds 20,000 cubic meters per second.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
