<HEADLINE> Offshore Oil Output More Than Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China Offshore Oil Nan Hai East
Corp (CONHE), produced 3.51 million tons of crude oil in the
South China Sea in the first Quarter of this year, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The figure was an encouraging 220,000 tons more than the
planned goal for that period, said the CONHE, one of four
subsidiaries of the China National Offshore Oil Corp.
</P>
<P>
The eastern South China Sea is one of China's major oil
producting areas. Experts say more than five billion tons of oil
are located in the 131,000 square kilometer area.
</P>
<P>
CONHE and its overseas partners so far have discovered fewer
than 10 percent of the estimated reserves.
</P>
<P>
CONHE plans to pump 33.78 million tons of crude oil during the
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) with an average annual output of
6.75 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In the previous 13 years, more than 38 overseas oil companies
have committed to explore and develop oil in the offshore
area. They include Esso, British Petroleum, Chevron, Agip, Shell,
Amoco and Phillips.
</P>
<P>
Liuhua 11-1, a field opened on March 29,1996, is China's
largest offshore oilfield. It is expected to produce 2.5 million
tons of oil annually during its peak years.
</P>
<P>
The Liuhua oilfield, run with US partners and 190 miles
southeast of Hong Kong, is estimated to contain more than 200
million tons of oil.
</P>
<P>
Huizhou 21-1 was China's first commercial offshore oilfield. It
began commercial production in the South China Sea in late
1989. Huizhou 26-1 started operation in November 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
