<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian Refugees Pose No Health Threat to Italy: Red Cross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Albanian refugees pose no health
risks to Italians, the head of the Italian Red Cross said here
today, and he denounced those using the issue as a scare tactic
for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
"Albanians are hardy people, and from what we have seen during
the medical check-ups given to all refugees when they arrive, some
of them have minor ailments or colds because of the conditions
they travel in, but that's it," Mariapia Garavaglia, commissioner
of the Italian Red Cross told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"So we must not be alarmist. Albanian refugees are not bringing
epidemics to Italy," Garavaglia said, adding that a mass
vaccination campaign had been launched by the Red Cross in the
Balkan nation in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Red Cross is caring for 7,880 refugees in 112 camps
throughout the country. The refugees fled Albania to escape the
violence and unrest gripping the nation.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner criticized those who "exploit this situation
during a campaign." He stressed, "We are dealing with forced
emigres, not voluntary ones."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Northern League deputy Alberto Lembo warned
against Albanians carrying diseases. "We don't want our regions
exposed to the risks of infection and epidemics," Lembo said.
</P>
<P>
Several northern city councils, notably Milan's administration,
have refused to accept any refugees, even though the government
has decided to spread the refugee burden more evenly across
Italy. So far, most of the refugees are in the south.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government set up a task force on Thursday to deal
with some 13,000 refugees who have fled to Italy since civil
unrest broke out in Albania in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Industry Flourishes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A recently concluded national work
conference on township enterprises mapped out a plan to guarantee
sustained and sound development of township industries, China
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese township enterprises are resultant from the reform and
opening policy, implemented 18 years ago, and they are conducive
to realistic situations in China's rural conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, owing to comparatively backward management and
technology, they also meet serious challenges and
difficulties. Many township enterprises use large quantities of
natural resources in pursuit of increased production.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, economists say they have affected the environment
to some extent.
</P>
<P>
They also lose ground in the market because they are not
competitive in terms of product variety, quality or
price. Township enterprises also are becoming less adaptable to
the market economy which requires effective promotional strategies.
</P>
<P>
In addition, many township enterprises are too small to be
profitable, lack the necessary competitive edge, have a misguided
product structure, suffer from poor management and heavy debts.
</P>
<P>
These problems prevent the enterprises from optimal development.
</P>
<P>
The conference focused on scientific research and application
in township enterprises to develop more high-tech products in the
future. With this, they are expected to improve overall standards
in management, sales and service.
</P>
<P>
Doumen, a historical town situated in the city of Shaoxing in
east China's Zhejiang Province, is a good example of a town that
has attracted foreign capital to bolster local economy.
</P>
<P>
Last year the town, whose population is 46,000, produced 2.03
billion yuan (245 million US dollars) worth of gross domestic
product, of which 1.81 billion yuan was contributed by the
township industry. It is listed as one of the 100 most developed
towns in the province.
</P>
<P>
The local government has strengthened its efforts to attract
overseas investment, and three joint ventures with a combined
investment of 5.93 million US dollars have been set up last
year. Fifteen foreign-funded enterprises are operating in the town
now.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
