<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin America over the past few days:
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's price index stood at 1.6 percent
in March, the lowest figure since February of 1994 when the
present government took power.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Venezuela attributed the drop in prices
to the economic stabilization program implemented by the national
government.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine tax revenues rose to 4.548 billion
U.S. dollars in March, 8.8 percent higher than in March 1996 and
a third higher than the 3.4 billion dollars forecast by the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican exports to Mexico rose 225 percent to
64.9 million dollars last year following a free trade accord
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Mexico still enjoyed a trade surplus since its exports
to Costa Rica were 212 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's major exports were coconut oil, sugar and
confectionery, medicines and leather products.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama will get 60 million U.S. dollars this
week from the World Bank and 35 million dollars from the
International Monetary Fund, after fulfilling their requirements
by the March 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's exports of wine rose by half to 109,545
liters in the first quarter of 1997 over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- An international seminar will be held in Managua from
April 9 to 11, to discuss the impact of globalization on Central
America and the Caribbean, the challenges faced by the regional
enterprises, and the economic and social needs of this region.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian soybean exports rose 26 percent to a
record 4.54 million tons in the current harvest over the previous
harvest and was double the volume exported during the same period
last year. 
