<DOCNO> XIE19970405.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Economy Sees No Signs of Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's managers painted a gloomy
picture of the state of the country's economy in a survey released
by the Ministry of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Two thirds of the 1,849 managers polled by the ministry said
their companies were still making redundancies and saw little
signs of recovery in the economy which has been in crisis over the
last few years in the transition to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
More than half the managers, from a range of sectors including
chemicals, food, engineering and glass, reported a fall in output
and production capacity in the second half of last year over the
first half.
</P>
<P>
Some 84 percent reported falling demand for their products and
one in four companies complained of rising stocks of finished
goods in their warehouses.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two thirds of companies reported a fall in stocks of raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
But costs and prices were on the rise in the second half of
last year, with 66 percent of managers reporting increases in the
cost of raw materials, and 43 percent reporting increases in the
prices of their finished products.
</P>
<P>
As for financing, only 2.2 percent of the managers polled had
received foreign investment in the second half of 1996, with 7.2
percent attracting investment from domestic sources, down from
nine percent in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Four out of five enterprises relied on their own funds and six
percent used government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The sectors attracting the highest levels of investment were
the energy sector, 22 percent of which received some form of
investment, the chemical and petrochemical industry with 15.5
percent, the steel industry, 14.3 percent and light industry 11
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
