<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Leaves on Visit to Kuwait, Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Left here today on a six-day working visit to
Kuwait and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The visit is aimed at adding impetus to bilateral relations
between Malaysia and the two Gulf states, the Foreign Ministry
said earlier.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, leading a 15-member official delegation, will be in
Kuwait for three days during which the two countries are expected
to sign a double taxation avoidance agreement.
</P>
<P>
He will then proceed to Bahrain for a three-day visit during
which he will deliver a keynote address at the Gulf Economic Forum
and have a meeting with the Bahraini Chamber of Commerce and
Bankers.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has good relations with these two countries. It has
signed economic and technical cooperation, cultural and
scientific, investment guarantee, trade and air services
agreements with Kuwait since the establishment of diplomatic
relations between the two nations in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is now Malaysia's fifth largest trading partner in West
Asia with bilateral trade amounting to 296 million ringgit (about
118.4 million U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Bahrain signed agreements on economic and
technical cooperation and on cultural and scientific cooperation
in 1975 and an air services agreement in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Total trade between Malaysia and Bahrain amounted to about 100
million ringgit (about 40 million dollars) last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
