<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (3-4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (3-4) in
a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What is the relationship between the Basic Law and
the Sino-British Joint Declaration?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Both the Basic Law and the Sino-British Joint
Declaration are documents of great historic importance. The
Sino-British Joint Declaration is a diplomatic convention reached
by the Chinese and British governments through diplomatic
negotiations on the settlement of the Hong Kong question left over
from history.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law, on the other hand, is a legal document of the
PRC enacted in accordance with the country's Constitution. It
represents, in the form of law, China's resumption of exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong and its administration of Hong Kong
after 1997 in accordance with the policy of "one country, two
systems".
</P>
<P>
Both the Joint Declaration and the Basic Law contain two basic
points: the return of Hong Kong to China and the maintenance of
Hong Kong's stability and prosperity. How to achieve these
goals? Their achievement has to rely on the "one country, two
systems" mechanism and a series of special policies worked out in
accordance with the concept of "one country, two systems". With
the enactment of the Basic Law, the Chinese government's 12 basic
policies regarding Hong Kong have been enshrined in the form of
law, in concrete legal terms. In legal terms also does the law
reflect the spirit of the Sino-British Joint Declaration.
</P>
<P>
Question: How does the Basic Law reflect the policy of "one
country, two systems?"
</P>
<P>
Answer: In content, the Basic Law from beginning to end
embodies the principles of "one country, two systems", "rule of
Hong Kong by Hong Kong people" and "a high degree of autonomy for
Hong Kong." For instance, in its provisions about the relationship
between the central government and the Hong Kong SAR, the Basic
Law stipulates that, on the premise of safeguarding national
sovereignty and the practicing of a socialist system in the
mainland, the current capitalist system and lifestyle of Hong Kong
will remain unchanged for 50 years. The central authorities will
be responsible only for Hong Kong's defence, foreign and other
affairs as prescribed by law. All powers that can be relegated to
the Hong Kong SAR will be given to the Hong Kong SAR, which will
have an unprecedentedly high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution of China, the National People's
Congress and its Standing Committee have the power to interpret
laws, including the Basic Law. However, in order that the Hong
Kong SAR enjoy an integral, independent judicial power, the NPC
Standing Committee will authorise the court of the Hong Kong SAR,
in adjudicating cases, to interpret provisions of the Basic Law
dealing with matters that fall within the autonomous powers of the
region. Only with regard to provisions of the Basic Law that
concern powers of the central government and the relationship
between the central government and the Hong Kong SAR is the court
of the Hong Kong SAR required to seek interpretation of relevant
provisions by the NPC Standing Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
