<HEADLINE> Australia and Italy Win Opening Singles in Davis Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Australia and Italy claimed the
victories in the opening singles in their Davis Cup quarter-final
clashes, but last year's finalists Sweden were given a tough
opening day by South Africa on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Australia dominated the flu-hit Czech Republic in Adelaide with
their big-servers Mark Philippoussis and Patrick Rafter proving
too powerful for Martin Damm and stand-in David Rikl.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, 24, who had got Australia off to such a fine start by
beating Cedric Pioline in their first-round clash against
champions France, was again able to get Australia off with a win
when he outplayed Damm 6-1, 7-6 (9/7), 4-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
The 1.94m Philippoussis, who has one of the world's fastest
serves, then slammed down 15 aces to hammer Rikl 6-1, 6-4, 2-6,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
Spain's hopes of translating this season's ATP tour successes
of their players to the Davis Cup floundered in Pesaro, Italy.
</P>
<P>
Omar Camporese shocked world number-eight Carlos Moya with a
stunning 6-7 (8/10), 6-7 (4/7), 6-1, 6-3, 6-3 comeback triumph.
</P>
<P>
Camporese, ranked a lowly 156 and standing in for Italian
number-one Andrea Gaudenzi, looked dead and buried after losing
two consecutive tiebreaks. But he found his service rhythm, and
Moya collapsed under the pressure to the delight of the Italian
crowd.
</P>
<P>
In the second rubber, Renzo Furlan also had to stage a comeback
and after trailing by two sets to one against Alberto Costa came
through to win 4-6, 6-3, 4-6, 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's world number-seven Thomas Enqvist cruised through his
opening rubber against South Africa's Grant Stafford 7-5, 2-6,
6-4, 6-1 in Vaxjo.
</P>
<P>
Stafford, ranked 69, briefly threatened by winning the second
set but Enqvist recovered to take the third and fourth in what was
mainly one-way traffic.
</P>
<P>
South Africa quickly levelled the tie at 1-1, however, when
world number 10 Wayne Ferreira saw off Jonas Bjorkman 6-3, 6-4,
2-6, 7-6 (7/3).
</P>
<P>
In the fourth quarterfinal in Newport, the United States were
pinning their singles hopes on Jim Courier and Andre Agassi
against Dutchmen Jan Siemerink and Sjeng Schalken respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
