<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Edge Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The rebound of technology shares
spurred a late rally on the New York Stock Exchange today despite
a weak bond market, where interest rates jumped toward a
nine-month high.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 48.72 points to
6,526.07, recovering from an early 72-point slide. That trimmed
the week's loss to 214.52 points, but the Dow is still nearly 560
points, or almost 8 percent shy of its all-time high at 7,085.16,
set on March 11.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin with the
volume reaching 537.24 million shares, more than 495.48 million in
the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market measures also turned higher in the afternoon.
The technology-laden Nasdaq market posting a sizable gain for the
second straight session amid some renewed interest in battered
computer-industry issues such as Intel and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 7.58, or about 1
percent, to 757.90. The Nasdaq composite index rose 22.97, or
nearly 2 percent, to 1,236.73.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 3.62 to 398.02, but the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 1.09 to 556.73.
</P>
<P>
Before today's open, interest rates jumped toward their highest
level since July in the bond market, where prices fell amid news
that the nation's unemployment rate fell for the second
consecutive month in March, pushing up hourly wage sharply.
</P>
<P>
The 5.2 percent unemployment rate reported by the Labor
Department was the lowest in five months and another sign of the
economy's brisk growth.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
soared to nearly 7.16 percent before settling at about 7.12
percent. The long-bond yield hasn't finished a day at that level
since last summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
