<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Senate to Ratify Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today urged the Senate to ratify the treaty banning all chemical
weapons by the deadline of April 29.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony outside the White House, Clinton said,
"If the Senate fails to ratify the convention before it enters
into force, our national security... and our economic security
will suffer."
</P>
<P>
The convention, which were signed by 161 countries in 1993 in
Paris, has been ratified by 70 countries so far and will take
effect as of April 29 with or without U.S. approval.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will ban the development, production, acquisition,
stockpiling, retention and transfer of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. Senate fails to ratify it by the deadline, the U.S.
will have no role in its implementation and U.S. chemical
companies could face sanctions, supporters say.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the rally, former Secretary of State James Baker
said, "If we fail to ratify the Chemical Weapons Convention, we
will be sending a clear signal of retreat from international
leadership both to our allies and our enemies alike."
</P>
<P>
The rally was also attended by U.S. Vice President Al Gore,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Defense Secretary William
Cohen and some senior officials from former U.S. administrations.
</P>
<P>
Opponents led by Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, insist that the convention does not serve
well the U.S. interests and vow to block it from ratification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
