<HEADLINE> Greek Inflation Drops to 6 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Greece's inflation sharply fell
from 6.6 percent in February to 6 percent in March this year, a
Greek government official announced today.
</P>
<P>
Yiannos Papantoniou, minister of national economy and finance,
said that the latest drop in inflation was out of expectations for
the government which had hoped for an annual rate of 6.2 percent
at the most.
</P>
<P>
The figures released by the National Statistics Service showed
that the sharp drop should be contributed to the rise of consumer
price index in March by only 2.2 percent, compared to 2.7 percent
in the same month last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Greek government's target of a 4.5
percent inflation this year, three percentage points lower than
inflation last year, had been half-achieved in the first quarter
of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
