<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Council Reprimands Libya on Violating Air Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today reprimanded Libya for a recent violation of the mandatory
U.N. air embargo.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Ambassador Antonio Monteiro, council president for
April, said in a statement that the flight of a Libyan-registered
aircraft from the Libyan capital Tripoli to Jeddah of Saudi Arabia
was a "clear violation of council resolution 748 of 31 March
1992."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council considered the act as "totally
unacceptable" and called on Libya to refrain from any further such
violations, he said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"The council will review the matter should further violations
occur," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council imposed mandatory sanctions, including a
ban on all international flights, on Libya in 1992 for failing to
extradite two men wanted by Britain and the United States for the
1988 mid-air bombing of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland,
which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Libya has denied the charges and refused to hand over the two
men to the West, but has expressed its willingness to surrender
them to a neutral court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
